Mewari Phagan
Since ancient times, the arrival of the king of seasons, spring, has infused new life into the entire creation, both the inert and the living.
In every region of our country, spring has been welcomed in its own unique way since the beginning.
By reading old cultural texts, it becomes clear that in ancient times many festivals were celebrated during the spring season.
Many legends, plays, and epic poems have been written about spring festivals, forest celebrations, and related events.
The joy, enthusiasm, and emotions of spring and the rainy season have been described so extensively that no other season has received such praise.
If one looks for descriptions of nature in literature, one finds hardly any name other than spring and the rainy season.
Seasons do exist.
The rainy season, filled with countless virtues and a giver of life, happiness, and prosperity, still was not granted the title of “king of seasons”; that crown was bestowed upon spring.
During these days, agility fills the body, enthusiasm fills the mind, joy flows through the heart, and an air of carefree merriment prevails—so much so that poets crowned spring as king, placed it on the highest literary throne, and worshipped it with poetry.
In truth, this is what a season truly is.
Farmers bow their heads before the earth; after enduring the winter cold, green fields flourish and granaries fill with grains.
The tall wheat stalks standing firm instill confidence in farmers who fought winter’s chill, while dreams sparkle in their eyes as crops sway under the burden of produce.
Yellow mustard fields stretch as far as the eye can see, spreading beauty like gardens and lifting farmers’ spirits.
They forget all their toil.
The exhaustion of twelve months of labor melts away in spring, and lamps of new hope for the coming year are lit.
During these days, the very colors of creation begin to change.
After three months of harsh cold, nature stretches, awakens, and shakes off its lethargy.
Dry branches shed lifelessness, trees regain vitality, and fresh red leaves bow gently as if offering respect.
Cuckoos, silent since the monsoon, open their throats and begin to sing.
The forest adorns itself like a newly dressed bride, draped in red blossoms of the flame tree.
Creepers begin to hang gracefully from tree branches.
Buds prepare to bloom, inviting bees to gather pollen.
Intoxicated by nectar, bees whirl joyfully around lotuses.
Sometimes they whisper into buds’ ears, sometimes they remain imprisoned in lotus hearts all night.
Ducks splash playfully in the water.
Deer leap joyfully across field boundaries.
Peacock feathers shine brilliantly, newly molted and vibrant.
New mango blossoms emerge, carrying messages of hope and joy to parrots and cuckoos.
The season begins with Basant Panchami.
Wheat stalks, mustard flowers, and mango blossoms are artistically arranged in water-filled vessels; plates of colored powder are prepared, drums resound at dawn, and songs proclaim: “Spring has arrived—come, play joyfully together.”
Indeed, men and women awaken to celebration.
Soon, spring-colored garments and scarves announce that for two months they will live in harmony with nature.
People rush to the temple of Istarinathji, shed their winter blankets, don yellow garments, shower devotees with colored powder, and command joyfully, “Go, play Phagan!”
Festivities begin in full splendor.
As Phagan arrives, women gather together, expressing heartfelt joy through song: “Phagan has come to Mewar—color me in its hues.”
Many long-cherished desires are fulfilled.
Reconciliation with the estranged becomes a special tradition of this season.
Skilled women coax their offended husbands back with playful gestures, veils drawn low, fingers on lips, teasing promises of drinks and celebration.
Many are indeed persuaded.
In truth, this month belongs to dancing, singing, laughter, music, and celebration.
Men bound by rigid customs break free and surrender themselves to the festive flow.
Social restraints are cast aside as groups dance and sing freely.
Distinctions of high and low are forgotten.
Even those bound by strict moral codes become carefree; as for tribal communities living close to nature, there is no need to ask.
They express emotions with simplicity and freedom, singing day and night.
Villagers ride elephants and parade through the streets playing Phagan.
Women stand atop rooftops with buckets and pots of colored water.
As rooftops align with elephant backs, women joyfully drench everyone below.
Water splashes from vessels hanging on elephants’ backs onto the women.
The wealthy play with luxurious colored powder balls.
Light floral balls made of marigolds and soft petals are gently tossed so as not to hurt tender bodies.
When these strike, they burst like flowers, scattering color.
Targets are carefully aimed with precision.
This form of Phagan is truly grand.
Flower-based Phagan is also played.
Heaps of flowers mixed with fragrant dust are thrown playfully.
To today’s readers, this may sound like a tale, yet many still alive have played such games.
Plucking roses daily from gardens was once ordinary.
Even today, roses are cultivated.
Water-splashing Phagan remains especially beloved.
Men and women splash water on one another using buckets.
Handling a bucket skillfully is an art.
Elders lament that today’s youth no longer know this art.
They hurl water clumsily, splattering walls and floors.
The elderly laugh and say, “Son, this is how Phagan is played.”
In the month of Chaitra, roses bloom, flame trees blaze, forests turn green, jasmine blossoms, neem flowers appear, and fields glow red with blossoms.
Girls eagerly gather flowers for worship and decoration.
Groups of ten or twenty roam forests and gardens collecting flowers.
Singing as they go, they decorate pots artistically and gather by the pond embankments.
They gaze at reflections of palaces and balconies mirrored in the water and sing: “High stands Rana’s palace, below lies Pichola’s shore.”
Amidst these scenic hills, floating waters, and homeland love, songs of longing pour forth: “Why should I go abroad when my heart belongs here?”
Roses begin to bloom.
At that time, buds burst open with audible snaps.
As if God Himself rests among rose fields, savoring spring’s beauty.
When buds bloom, they release sweet fragrance.
Above, cuckoos sing from mango branches, sweetening sleep.
Mango blossoms drift gently down.
Fragrant winds grow heavy, weighing down eyelids.
Parrot flocks spread green wings, ready to fly.
During this season, the Gangaur festival arrives.
“Let us play Gangaur,” the refrain echoes day and night.
Singing and dancing continue endlessly.
Until late night, women twirl in ghagras, bells jingling.
Married women plead for husbands’ safe return, singing of longing and devotion.
They sit in balconies singing softly: “May I adorn like your henna, my beloved.”
Their sweet voices intoxicate even cuckoos into song.
During this festival, cuckoos’ throats fill with passion, and bees sweeten nectar with honey.
The pain of love’s arrows lingers within.
There is impatience of new leaves and intoxication of youth.
Only those who swim in the lake of emotion can know its joy.
God alone knows who listens, but dancers surely sway, cups of liquor in hand.
Here, Phagan has seven forms.
People celebrate according to age, status, and taste.
The elephant festival of the Ranas was especially famous.
Heaps of color on elephants’ heads created spectacular scenes.
Even in moments of joy, Rajput warriors cherished valor.
They played Phagan on horseback.
With reins in one hand and color in the other, riders charged forward.
Hooves kicked clouds of color into the air; riders hurled gulal with precision, thrilling all who watched.
The sand dunes blazed fiercely
The hot scorching wind blew so harshly that it seemed to burn the hair inside the ears
Below, the earth scorched; above, the sky burned
The Sodha youth sat in the shade of a khejri tree, burning from within and without, on both sides
The outer heat ignited flames inside his heart, like the blaze of a burning Holi
The midday sun’s sharp rays struck his head, blinding his eyes, yet he felt no awareness of it
He was so deeply drowned in thought that all four directions seemed the same to him
Today a man arrived with a message from the future father-in-law of his betrothed
If the wedding is to happen, fifteen hundred rupees must be brought within three days, otherwise on Akha Teej your bride will be married to someone else
Hearing this, flames rose in the eyes of the Sodha youth
His hand automatically fell upon the hilt of his sword
He bit his lips between his teeth
If his bride were married to another, for whom he had paid the ritual coconut ten years ago and filled his lap with hope, and while planning the wedding both parents had died
Silence had fallen upon the house
Who would tend the fields, the cows and buffaloes
Where would he bring fifteen hundred rupees from now
Without paying this money, his bride would be married to another, the bride he had dreamed of for ten long years, who on Akha Teej would be given to someone else
Blood surged into the eyes of the Sodha youth
Until today, for such a bride, even if heads were cut off, how could he live while his bride married another, never
Uncle Bora, my honor lies in your hands
I have always protected honor
Tell me then, which fields should I sell to arrange fifteen hundred
Is there anything left to mortgage
Do I have anything at all
The honor of a Rajput, only the hilt of a sword remains with me
Then brother, look at some other moneylender’s door
The Sodha writhed in pain
Look uncle, in my childhood itself, bit by bit, through false and true documents, you have taken everything from my house
You did not even leave a single shard behind
I gave you everything, and whatever you asked, I was ready to give
But at this moment, protect my household’s honor
If my bride goes to another, it is equal to dying while alive
Placing this sword on the head of Jagdamba, I swear I will repay every coin washed in milk
Whatever interest you set
At this moment give me the money
If he is truly a Rajput’s son, he will do this much
If I sign on the bond, will you put your signature on it
I can give my head, but for now protect my honor
The merchant prepared the bond and moved forward
He picked up the ink-stained pen resting behind his ear and held it in his hand
Read the bond, and if you are truly a Rajput, then sign it
He read the bond, kept it ready, that I will not repay this money with interest until my wedding takes place, and I will treat the bride as my sister
Pressing his lips between his teeth, sparks flying in the night, eyes blazing, he signed it
The Sodha house that had been silent for years, today a lamp burned in the bride’s pavilion
Today a lamp burned in the bride’s pavilion
The house eaten by termites and fallen beams was plastered and smiled
After many years today, anklets echoed in the bride’s home
The cart brought in dowry from her parents’ house, filling the home with household goods
Sodha sat down to eat, and the bride, holding a woven fan in her hand, began fanning the air
Her bangles clinked softly with her hands
Today the entire house was busy with one thing or another
Affection shone in the bride’s eyes, but seriousness filled Sodha’s eyes
That meal passed somehow
Sodha wished to speak, but words would not come, how could he speak before her
As the meal ended, the bride quickly rose and began pouring water over his hands, when Sodha’s gaze fell upon the bond, glistening with sweat under her veil, striking his eyes like a rock cliff, his hands trembled
The stream of water from the pot spilled onto the ground
Night fell, time for sleep arrived
They lay on the bedding brought from her parents’ house
Quickly drawing his sword from its sheath, he placed it between them and turned his face away to sleep
The bride trembled
Why is this, is someone angry with me
One, two, three, ten, fifteen nights passed
That very sword lay between them daily like a black serpent
By day he spoke and conversed, as if nectar flowed from his head and love dripped from his eyes, but as night fell not a word left his lips, nor did those same eyes even look toward her
Being so close all night yet feeling so distant
Being so distant by day yet feeling so close
The bride carefully observed Sodha’s behavior and thought deeply
Something was wrong
The moment he drew the sword and lay down, she bent and caught his feet, what fault do I have
Why are you angry with me
If there was a mistake, it was my parents who broke stones for money
Slowly falling tears reached Sodha’s feet
Who says I am angry with you
You are my wife, the mistress of my home
Pulling her hands away from his feet, Sodha spoke
Then why, when living so close, are you so distant from me
Two creases formed on Sodha’s forehead
You really wish to know
Then take and read this bond
Raising the wick of the lamp, trembling in its light, she began reading the bond
As she read, light awakened upon her face
With innocence and satisfaction her face began to glow
Holding the bond, breathing freely, she said there is no worry in this, I was only afraid of your anger
Following the vow was very difficult
At dawn itself, gathering their small belongings and household items, placing them before Sodha, she said sell these, buy a horse, repaying debt is the foremost duty
If we sit at home, farming will seem good
A Rajput gains honor through service
I will serve some king
Should I leave you at your parents’ house
Where would you live
Why the parents’ house
Wherever you are, there I am, bring two horses
But how will you endure this hardship with me
Why not, am I not a Rajput’s daughter, have I not tasted the hardships of a Rajputani, I know how to tie a sword like you, I have ridden my father’s horse myself
Think about it
I have thought it through
Sodha kept gazing at her brightly shining face
The sun had climbed one and a quarter hand spans high in the sky
From the foothills of Chittor, two horses ran side by side, racing straight toward Chittor.
Two young riders of the same age, dressed alike, drove their horses hard with knees pressed low.
The spear in the hand flashed repeatedly in the rays of the rising sun.
The swords tied at their waists scraped and clashed along with the galloping horses.
Who could say by looking that one of them was a woman.
At that moment, the Rajputani looked like a young warrior filled with valor.
A toothed bangle adorned her hand, her veil gone, her wrists bare.
With strong hands she held the spear firmly, gripping it with control.
The shy, gentle voice once like a koel’s call had now turned into a bold, resonant tone.
The cheeks that used to blush behind the veil were no longer hidden.
Sharp brilliance burst from her face like rays of the sun.
With a flush rising, love overflowed from her eyes.
It was as if she had taken the very form of Goddess Durga.
Urging the horse on, she reached the foothills of Chittor in a single surge.
They halted near Rana ji’s gate.
As his eyes fell upon them, his gaze paused for a moment on the pair.
Pulling the reins, he asked, which Rajput are you.
Why have you come here.
With a measure of millet, O provider of grain.
Be present with us in the hunt.
Saluting, both youths turned their horses and followed behind.
A fierce chase of the boar began.
The boar ran ahead, while behind it, spear in hand, the lead rider drove the horse at full force.
The lone boar, striking wildly with its tusks, broke the encirclement and burst out.
Cries rose from all sides, it has gone, it is escaping, strike it.
All horses turned toward the boar when suddenly one horse surged forward like lightning, the rider struck with the spear, tearing open the belly, ripping the entrails, piercing straight through.
Watching from afar, Rana ji praised them at once.
Wiping away sweat, the rider dismounted, saluted, then mounted again and returned.
Who could imagine that the one who felled the wild boar with a spear was a woman.
Pleased, Rana ji commanded that from today both brothers would serve at his palace gate.
Accepting the command of the provider, they took up the service.
The rain of Sawan fell with a rippling sound.
The pond spread out like a sheet.
Frogs croaked loudly.
On one side lay darkness, above it the black monsoon night with dark clouds spread everywhere.
Lightning flashed so fiercely that eyes shut tight and could not open.
Thunder roared as if it would crush the earth itself.
It was a dark and terrifying night where one could not see hand before hand.
Rana ji slept, while the two Rajputs stood guard.
They held naked swords in their hands.
When lightning flashed, it shimmered against the gleam of their bare swords.
At midnight, Rana ji fell asleep, but sleep did not come to the queen’s eyes.
Half awake, she watched the wondrous union of nature’s forms.
Both Rajputs stood before the gate with drawn swords.
Lightning flashed in the north, and the Rajputani remembered how her homeland shines with such flashes.
With that memory, many thoughts returned to her.
To earn a living, I perform a man’s duty, standing guard at midnight in a foreign land.
Other women sleep behind closed doors in their homes.
I stand awake through the night holding a naked sword.
Suddenly, from nearby, a bird called out, pee pee.
The weakness of a woman’s heart stirred.
Where are you, beloved.
There is much hardship, but what can be done.
My fate lies neither in union nor in separation.
I am like the chakwa bird, sitting far away and enduring separation.
I remain together day and night, yet am tormented by separation.
Her restraint broke.
Quietly she placed her hand on Sodha’s shoulder, as if struck by lightning.
Both of them trembled.
Sodha came to his senses and said, be careful, Rajputani.
The Rajputani steadied herself.
The homeland is lost, we are in a foreign land.
He is a husband, yet appears in the form of a brother.
When will I return to my land, when will he become my husband.
The queen, half asleep, watched this entire scene.
At dawn, the queen told Rana ji that there was some difference between these Sodha brothers.
Why, is there something wrong.
Shall I have their heads cut off.
It is not a matter of cutting, but of joining.
One of them is a woman.
Queen, do not speak foolishly.
Such a face, such eyes, such manliness, could that ever belong to a woman.
Believe it or not, as you wish.
One of them is a woman and she is in distress.
How shall we find out.
I will test her.
You sit behind the screen and watch, have both brothers summoned.
Milk was set to boil on the hearth and a signal was given for her to come out.
Seeing the milk boil over, the Rajputani cried out, the milk is boiling, the milk is boiling.
Sodha signaled with his eyes as the queen came out and asked, daughter, tell the truth, who are you.
Do not hide it from me.
The Rajputani placed her head upon the queen’s chest and revealed herself.
She narrated the entire story to Sodha.
Rana ji was greatly pleased.
I will send the money of your debt with interest to your village with an escort.
Stay here and establish your household.
Sodha folded his hands and said, O provider, your command rests upon my head, but until I repay the debt with my own hands, I will not tear the bond, how can I fulfill your order otherwise.
Grant me guidance.
Rana ji gave guidance along with ample means to repay the debt and settle the household.
The thought of the joy of that full-moon night is exceedingly sweet.
Among Indian billionaires, one third are Rajasthani.
The world-renowned Forbes magazine, in its March 2011 issue, published details of 1,210 billionaires worldwide, among whom fifty-five were Indians.
At that time, one billion dollars was valued as equal to four thousand four hundred eighty crore rupees.
Among those fifty-five billionaires, twenty-six belonged to the Vaishya community, whose population in India is only one percent.
These Vaishya billionaires are mostly from Rajasthan and Gujarat.
In this Forbes disclosure, the names of expatriate Rajasthanis appeared, and their number among the fifty-five Indians was eleven.
The ranking was as follows: the richest Indian, Lakshmi Niwas Mittal, ranked sixth in the world, owning 31.1 billion dollars.
Second and third were Gujarat’s Mukesh Ambani with 27 billion dollars and Wipro chairman Azim Premji with 16.8 billion dollars.
Fourth and fifth positions were held by expatriate Rajasthanis Shashi Ravi Ruia with 15.8 billion dollars and Savitri Jindal with 13.2 billion dollars.
The sixth and eighth positions were held by Gujarat’s Gautam Adani with ten billion dollars and Anil Ambani with 8.8 billion dollars.
The seventh position was held by expatriate Rajasthani Kumar Mangalam Birla, with a net worth of 9.2 billion dollars.
At the ninth position was Sunil Mittal of the Vaishya community with 8.3 billion dollars, and the tenth position was held by Parsi community member Adi Godrej with 7.3 billion dollars.
In this list, the next position included another expatriate Rajasthani.
Among them, the eleventh position was held by Anil Agarwal of the Vedanta Group with 6.4 billion dollars.
The twelfth position was occupied by Dilip Shanghvi of Sun Pharma with 6.1 billion dollars.
The fourteenth position was held by Subhash Chandra Goel of the Zee Group with 2.1 billion dollars.
The twenty-first position was occupied by Indu Jain of the Times of India with 2.6 billion dollars.
The twenty-fifth position was held by Deshbandhu Gupta of Lupin with 2.1 billion dollars.
The twenty-sixth position was occupied by Alok Lohia of Indorama with two billion dollars.
The thirtieth position was held by Venugopal Dhoot of Videocon.
He had a net worth of 1.9 billion dollars.
In this sequence, the thirty-fourth position was held by Rahul Bajaj of the Bajaj Group with 1.6 billion dollars, the thirty-sixth position by Brijmohan Munjal of Hero Motors with 1.5 billion dollars, and the thirty-eighth position by Ajay Piramal with 1.4 billion dollars.
After them, the forty-first position was occupied by R. P. Goenka with 1.3 billion dollars.
The forty-third position was held by Rakesh Jhunjhunwala with 1.2 billion dollars.
The forty-third position was also occupied by B. K. Modi with 1.1 billion dollars.
The forty-eighth position was held by Mangal Prabhat Lodha with 1.1 billion dollars.
The fifty-first position was occupied by Mofatraj Munot of the Kalpataru Group with one billion dollars.
Viewed this way, out of the fifty-five individuals in this list, more than nineteen are expatriate Rajasthanis.
The second largest representation belongs to Gujaratis, numbering ten.
Apart from the Vaishya community, there are three Parsis, two Muslims, two Sikhs, and others from different communities, but there is not a single person from the Scheduled Castes or Scheduled Tribes.
From many other states of the country, no one has been included in this list.
Naval Bajaj has been elected as the Chairman of the Indo–Canada Chamber of Commerce.
A native of Sikar, Rana Canada’s Vice President Navalji Bajaj was elected as the twenty-fifth Chairman of the Indo–Canada Chamber of Commerce at its annual general meeting held in Toronto.
Three years ago, he joined this organization as a director, and the very next year,
he became Vice President, and after that he assumed the post of Chairman.
His priority is to strengthen trade relations between India, Canada, and other countries.
He focuses on promoting business and improving facilities.
Navalji Bajaj, as a certified business advisor in Canada, is associated with the financial and strategic planning of the 7-Eleven Canada organization.
Holding a Master of Engineering, a Master of Business Administration, and a Bachelor of Law degree, Navalji has also been associated in India with IIM, SSM, and the Management Association of the Gujarat Chamber of Commerce.
Rana Canada President Y. K. Sharma and Media Chairman Prem Bhandari congratulated Navalji Bajaj on being elected ICCC Chairman and described it as a matter of pride for all expatriate Rajasthanis.
In these elections of the Indo–Canada Chamber of Commerce, three other expatriate Rajasthanis—Jagdish Bajaj, Avi Goyal, and Mukesh Bhardwaj—were elected to the post of directors.
Welcome to granting voting rights to expatriates.
Rana’s Media Chairman Prem Bhandari welcomed the Government of India’s decision to grant voting rights to overseas Indians and to create a special voter list, stating that this would strengthen expatriates’ connection with the soil of their homeland.
He said that when they themselves go to vote, they will first apply to have their names included in the overseas voter list.
The account of Jagdev Panwar.
The Malwa region, within which lies the city of Dhar.
There, Panwar Udayadit ruled, and he had two queens.
From one queen, the chief queen Bagheli, a prince named Rindhaval was born.
From the other queen, Solankani, who was less favored, a prince was born and was named Jagdev.
Dark-complexioned, radiant in spirit, and Rindhaval was the lord of the kingdom.
After twelve months, Jagdev was born.
There, King Udayadit asked his attendants whether a son had been born to Solankani.
Then the king said that in this world nothing is equal to a son.
Then the attendants said, “But Your Majesty, she never comes to the court.”
Then the king sent his servants and summoned Jagdev.
Then Jagdev came to the court, wearing a patched garment, with a turban worth one rupee on his head, bracelets on his hands, and he bowed respectfully.
The king embraced him, seated him beside himself, and asked, “Son, why are you wearing such clothes?”
Then the prince said, “There is a fault in my penance; I was born in the royal household.”
But in the Malwa region of the king, he placed a slight burden on him, and therefore he gave one village to his mother.
This was exactly according to what he deserved.
And in his mother’s hands lay the responsibility of royal duties.
Because of this, the village became prosperous.
He was given a small revenue share, and for food and clothing, servants and maidservants were employed, and all these needs were met from the same village’s revenue.
But for clothing, the allowance was sufficient.
The king took care of this and said, “One and a quarter rupees shall always be yours, one rupee for your meals, and seventeen rupees for household expenses.”
The king instructed the attendants to always give him two rupees.
Then Jagdev submitted a request, “O King, you have already given me a reward, but Mother Goddess bestows great grace; whatever is written cannot be changed.”
Then the king summoned the treasurer, asked for a pouch, and instructed that good clothing be prepared and that he should live with dignity.
Then the prince was given advice.
The prince went to his mother, gave her the pouch, and told her to prepare good clothes and live with dignity.
The prince went to his mother with the pouch and told her the entire truth.
Some men of Bagheli were sitting there, watching and listening to the conversation.
They went and said that today the king showed great affection to Jagdev, gave him two rupees daily, and also gave him a pouch.
Hearing this, jealousy rose in the Bagheli faction.
Then the queen searched and summoned the king inside, paid her respects, and sat on the throne.
Then the queen angrily said, “Why have you given something to the son of the less-favored queen today?”
Then the king said, “Solankani is less favored, but the son is still a son.”
Rindhaval is the rightful heir, but Jagdev also came into my sight as worthy.
If he turns out to be a strong Rajput, then what?” said Bagheli.
She said, “He was born under an inauspicious fate.”
“He who has dark letters in his destiny, call back the pouch.”
Then the king said, “I have given it for his virtues.”
“Now ask him and see why I gave it.”
At that time, Mandavgadh’s ruler, Mandu Raja, served Udayadit.
The messengers who brought letters arrived hurriedly.
But the king did not become angry and kept both princes nearby.
Now Jagdev was summoned and brought before them.
Among the people, murmuring spread, and in the court Rindhaval was favored.
Jagdev stayed at home and remained there.
Two years passed.
There was Gaur, another serious king.
With his retinue, he came to Jagdev.
One elephant, nine horses, coconuts adorned with gold and silver were brought, along with priests and attendants.
They arrived at Dhar.
They offered gifts, performed formal rituals, and then the priest and attendants together asked about the offering of the coconut.
Then the Gond priest said, “Our king has decided to present the coconut to Prince Jagdev.”
He said that Prince Jagdev should be seated on the throne, the tilak applied, and the coconut presented.
Hearing this, everyone became silent.
They stood up.
There was great fear of Bagheli.
Everyone went and told Bagheli that the coconut was meant for Jagdev.
Then Bagheli became angry and furious, shouting that her ears would burst with rage.
“My son is the one for whom the coconut has come.”
She said, “Go and tell that maid to kill him, and arrange Rindhaval properly as the heir.”
“Otherwise, I will stop serving you.”
Then the priests and attendants agreed to give money to the Gond priests and attendants and said that Jagdev was born of the less-favored queen, whose mother is not the chief queen, so give the coconut to him.
Then after taking the money, the coconut was tied to Rindhaval and the tilak was applied.
Trumpets were sounded.
Then the priest said, “Once let me see Jagdev with my own eyes, then I will inquire from Bagheli.”
Jagdev was brought; the priest and minister observed him and saw that his head bore ascetic signs, his spirit was radiant, and he appeared enlightened, but his destiny was written differently.
Now advice was sought.
Then he was honored with ceremonial clothing and sent away.
After that he returned to Godawati.
He met King Gambhir.
The coconut was given to Rindhaval.
He is royal and radiant, but he cannot compete with Jagdev’s spiritual brilliance.
Even without fine attire, Rindhaval appeared like the moon before the sun.
But destiny is stronger.
Then the king said, “Many mistakes happen; what is given cannot be taken back, and there is no second option.”
Then the astrologer was summoned to fix the marriage date at Dhar, and another attendant was sent with a letter, in which it was written that Jagdev must be brought along, and if he does not come, the marriage will not take place.
A man came to Dhar to take the marriage proposal.
The letter was given into the attendant’s hands.
After reading the letter, it was handed to Bagheli.
Then Bagheli said angrily, “Strike hard and take Kalyan along.”
Preparations for the wedding procession were made.
Then Jagdev was informed, “Prince, prepare for the journey.”
Jagdev replied, “Without ornaments, attire, and a horse befitting royalty, it would not be proper for me to go.”
Then from the royal storehouse he was given bracelets, pearls, a necklace, sacred thread, garlands of pearls, and many attendants.
In this manner a grand procession was formed; there is no need to describe it further, thousands of horsemen rode along, and during the journey many halts were made.
At the fort of Chavda Rao, the prince was recognized as a ruler.
That ruler had restrained eyes, but the hearts of the people were open.
Much could be understood just by looking into his eyes.
He had a daughter named Veermati, the eldest princess.
Her marriage alliance was not easily found.
At that time the procession arrived.
Then King Rajji told Prince Bij that Jagdev is a prince of exceptional strength.
He is a Rajput; tomorrow the wedding rituals will be performed.
Bij accepted the command with respect, came to greet Prince Jagdev, and said, “Tomorrow morning, please accept the ceremonial feast.”
With much insistence, the feast was agreed upon.
When they arrived at the fort, the astrologer was called and the marriage date was confirmed.
At dawn, the auspicious wedding ceremony was held.
All decorations were completed.
The next day, Veermati’s turmeric ceremony was performed, and Lord Ganesh was installed.
On the third occasion, the groom’s feast took place.
After sunset, they dined and rose to perform the ritual washing, and then the wedding hour arrived; the priest told the attendants that Prince Jagdev was given his daughter.
Then the coconut ritual was performed, and four horses were sacrificed ceremonially.
The ceremonial gateway was erected, and the bride was welcomed; the attendants witnessed a grand event.
Some went directly to Godara, others proceeded through the ceremonial gate into the pavilion.
They completed the wedding circumambulations.
The ceremonial feast was held.
One elephant, twenty-five horses, a double-storied mansion, and maidservants were given.
At dawn, blessings were sought.
The marriage rites were completed.
Then they came to Toda.
The bride was seated in the chariot and sent with him.
The wedding procession departed.
When Jagdev reached Godara, news of the marriage spread.
King Gambhir saw Jagdev, and the priests and courtiers were very displeased, but destiny prevailed.
Now the wedding feast was given.
A mansion was granted, twenty-five horses, one elephant, and maidservants for eleven days were given.
Blessings were bestowed.
Then he arrived at Toda.
The bride was seated in the chariot and sent along.
When they reached the city, Bagheli learned of Jagdev’s marriage and felt great sorrow in her heart.
She said, “Everyone gives their daughter to that ill-fated man; who would even look at him?”
After that, a gathering was held.
There, the groom and bride bowed at the feet of the elders.
Ritual offerings to the deities were performed.
After a month, the groom and bride returned.
He took his daughter back.
When she went to her parental home, the dowry that was given matched what had accompanied her, and Jagdev kept it.
Thus eighteen years passed in Jagdev’s life.
Then King Udayadit arrived unexpectedly.
Prince Rindhaval came forward with a grand procession.
He bowed at his feet.
The merchants also bowed.
Among them, everyone paid respects, but Jagdev did not perform obeisance.
Seeing this, the king was very enthusiastic, sat on the throne in the audience hall, and commanded, “Where is Prince Jagdev?”
Then it was said, “Your Majesty, he is present in the Solanki quarters.”
Then servants were sent to summon him.
Then Jagdev came, wearing simple clothes, and bowed at his feet.
The king rose, embraced him to his chest, placed his hand on his head, seated him very close, and asked, “Prince, why are you wearing such clothes?”
Then the prince submitted, “Your Majesty, after you departed,
you had ordered two rupees daily for sustenance and household expenses.
Mother did not accept it, and without her permission the cook would not give food.
You yourself know this.
Without produce and income, how can provisions be maintained?”
Then the king granted bracelets, pearl necklaces, sacred threads, armlets, turbans, swords, shields, daggers, quivers, and arrows, all as gifts.
Then Jagdev paid respects repeatedly, folded his hands, and submitted,
“Your Majesty, I have received your kindness, but Mother Bagheli is not merciful to me.
If you visit Bagheli’s palace, all arrangements will have to be made.
After taking me from my residence, she will not let me stay.
Therefore, the order has been for me to live separately.”
Then the king said, “Even if Bagheli speaks, I consider Rindhaval and you as equal princes.
And again, I count you among my own sons.
I have given you my estate, and for your procession I have given you a special royal horse.”
Agricultural development in Rajasthan.
In every region, according to local conditions, attention must be given to vegetation development for animal fodder.
The state government has declared a sewan grass development belt in western Rajasthan, keeping in view the drought-resistant qualities of sewan grass.
Once established, this grass can survive for years despite severe drought.
The Agriculture Minister Burdak stated before agricultural scientists
that concrete suggestions have been given to use the special traits of sewan grass through genetic science for developing improved varieties of pearl millet.
For this purpose, research is needed at the ground level.
Today this may seem difficult, but considering the innovations that have occurred in agriculture so far, this possibility cannot be completely ruled out.
In the year 1954, he directly entered village panchayat elections from the fields.
He has contested the legislative assembly nearly ten times.
Agriculture Minister Harjiram Burdak has vast bitter and sweet experience of drought-prone farming in dry climatic conditions.
Three decades ago, due to the indiscriminate felling of the state tree khejri, pamphlets were issued to promote the importance of khejri in order to protect it from the harmful effects of its declining numbers.
Today, the Arid Forest Research Institute is working on a megaproject focused on the conservation of the highly useful khejri tree.
By widely promoting effective measures to save the drying khejri, the ecological baseline of the desert region can be preserved.
This year, the Bikaner Gaushala Federation has undertaken a campaign to raise ten million new khejri saplings.
Along with this, wildlife lovers and environmentalists from Nagaur,
Himtararam Bhambu is planting two hundred and fifty thousand saplings on government land in addition to private fields.
This has marked a milestone in agricultural forestry.
Rajasthan accounts for eighty percent of the country’s total guar cultivation area, but in terms of per-hectare productivity, it contributes only fifty-six percent of the national guar production.
The dry climate and uncertainty of rainfall are the main reasons for this.
According to retired pulse scientist Dr. Devendra Kumar of CAZRI,
by running a systematic guar production program in the state’s different regions,
locally developed varieties should be distributed according to regional demand.
This would help minimize crop losses caused by uncertain rainfall.
In this way, the average productivity of guar in the state can be increased to twelve quintals per hectare.
After a twelvefold increase in guar prices last year,
this year farmers are showing increased interest in sowing kharif guar.
However, guar seed is not available in the market even at a rate of six hundred rupees per kilogram.
It is clear that companies operating through buyback agreements are increasing transactions with farmers this year.
Traditional farmers, who used to move like puppets in the hands of nature, are now beginning to apply scientific practices.
Not only abroad, but progressive farmers within the country are also
deeply understanding the various reasons that make farming a loss-making venture and are adopting innovations.
Last year in September, in Jaipur, under the joint auspices of CITA and the state government,
twenty-eight progressive innovative farmers from across the country were honored with national-level awards.
Among them, four farmers were from Rajasthan.
On this occasion, the Union Agriculture Minister Sharad Pawar himself
thanked the Rajasthan government and, following this model,
announced that the next program would be held in Goa.
Pawar rightly said that in a country where water is valued more than ghee,
farmers still manage to obtain crops while walking on thorny paths.
In Rajasthan, abundant possibilities for agricultural development are clearly visible.
The farsighted and experienced state Agriculture Minister Burdak has received strong support from Chief Minister Ashok Gehlot and the Union Minister.
Being an elderly farmer himself, no proposal of Burdak can easily be rejected.
In the meeting of agriculture ministers from across the country, Burdak’s views were listened to and understood carefully.
In fact, the problem of drought exists not only in deserts but also in the hilly and plateau regions of many states.
And from region to region, farmers’ problems may outwardly appear different,
but fundamentally they are the same.
Therefore, to solve even the smallest problems of small farmers, around twenty types of government subsidy schemes have been implemented in the state.
Not only this, on the lines of the Jal Chetna Yatra, during the kharif season, agriculture department employees
and officers stay for a day at gram panchayat headquarters and provide information about all schemes.
Applications of eligible beneficiaries are filled and completed on the same day.
In fact, the government has succeeded in understanding
that educated farmers can adopt advanced farming techniques on their own.
But among poor farmer brothers, many rural people fail to take full advantage of government schemes.
Now the government has placed special emphasis on village-to-village outreach through agricultural fairs, widespread agricultural literature, and the distribution of low-cost or free agricultural inputs.
The meaningful results of all these efforts are now becoming visible.
The combined effect of wide publicity of government schemes, better implementation,
and the dedication of officials
is clearly visible in the success stories published in agricultural magazines.
Rajasthan, the largest state in the country, is dependent on the mercy of the monsoon.
Although Rajasthan accounts for about ten point forty-one percent of the country’s total area, it has only one percent of the nation’s total available surface water.
This is why, even after independence and despite all five-year plans,
Rajasthan’s share in national agricultural production is not as high
as it should be in proportion to its area.
Although two-thirds of the state, to the northwest of the Aravalli range, is completely arid,
before independence, the Ganga Canal and later the Indira Gandhi Canal project
brought significant increases in irrigated area and production in western border districts.
Even so, looking at the current agricultural situation in the state, there remains considerable scope for improvement.
It is another matter that over the last sixty years, almost all governments
have introduced many schemes from time to time for agricultural reforms.
But due to geographical disparities, social structures, and illiteracy, along with many other reasons,
Farmers in Rajasthan could not receive proper direction.
Rural innovation.
Arvind Sankhla of Mathania in Jodhpur, observing bumper carrot production and export potential from the Rampura region,
gradually developed a three-in-one carrot washing machine over time.
Along with saving labor and money, it produces well-cleaned bags of carrots.
It directly functions as a processing unit suitable for market supply.
Raisinghnagar’s Raisingh Daiya, using waste biomass and crop residue used as fuel,
developed a gasifier through which an average of nine kilowatts of energy can be generated from a single fuel source.
This energy is directly capable of operating electrical equipment.
Similarly, Ishaq Mohammed of Kachholi in Abu Sirohi, over the last ten to twelve years,
has developed improved varieties by innovating advanced agricultural techniques for fennel cultivation.
In fact, information available at local agricultural science centers
must be delivered to the right users through proactive initiative by agricultural scientists,
so that real practitioner farmers in the fields can correctly apply new principles.
Innovation in agriculture does not merely mean inventing a machine.
The state’s weekly agricultural newspaper, Haladhar Times, regularly dedicates a full page to innovation-driven farmers.
Among farmers adopting any kind of agricultural innovation or method,
honoring one farmer district-wise every year with the Haladhar Ratna award
reflects the true spirit of the government’s ATMA project.
Falling behind.
Rajasthani cinema.
From its foundation to the present, Rajasthan has been a leader in development in every field, but it lags far behind in producing films in its mother tongue, Rajasthani.
As a result, the Rajasthani film industry today appears to be searching for its own identity.
In its own home, comparatively better-made Rajasthani films have suffered neglect and remained backward.
There are many reasons behind the backwardness of films made in Rajasthani.
When films made in Rajasthani are compared with those made in other languages, a vast difference is visible in every aspect of filmmaking.
Rajasthani films appear weaker than films of other languages from every perspective.
Why has Rajasthani cinema still not been able to establish a strong and recognizable identity?
Taking this issue forward, Nandushree Minister discussed with people associated with Rajasthani cinema and examined various aspects of it.
Presented here are excerpts from that discussion.
These days Neelu is playing a prominent sister-in-law role in the Hindi television serial “Diya Aur Baati Hum” airing on Star Plus.
Neelu, who has played lead roles in many Rajasthani films, believes that dedicated people are needed to develop the Rajasthani film industry.
People who have an attachment to Rajasthan, no matter where they live, should come together and step forward for their mother tongue, Rajasthani.
Sandeep Vaishnav.
“From Thari Mhari to Layer Ma Bhatyani, it has taken almost a lifetime.”
Producer-director Sandeep Vaishnav, who has made ten Rajasthani films, says that
to preserve the existence of the Rajasthani film industry
and to take it forward, experienced filmmakers are needed.
The director is the captain of a film.
If the captain’s own steps falter, the team is bound to lose.
K. C. Malu.
Director K. C. Malu of the film Veena says that in Rajasthani films, the use of songs and music is merely a formality and an act of tokenism.
At the very steps where producers should invest money, such as music, they do not pay proper attention.
Due to weak music, films turn out to be weak, and instead of songs becoming immortal, they fail to leave an impression on audiences even during the film’s run.
Sunny Agarwal.
“Jai Jeen Mata, my Shyam Dhani the giver, devotee Dhanna Jat,”
“Bless us, Shri Sudha Mata, and make things as simple as brewing tea for Bapuji.”
Rajasthani film actor Sunny Agarwal says that
the attitude of the state government towards Rajasthani films has been negative since the very beginning.
Even so, several Rajasthani films have been made and have been released.
Mohan Kataria.
Producer, director, and actor Mohan Kataria says that
to nurture and advance the industry, along with good producers,
there is also a need for good films so that Rajasthani audiences get to watch films of their choice.
Mukesh Tak.
New producer Mukesh Tak of the Rajasthani film “Chundri Odhasi Mhari Beera” says that
he made the film with the objective of giving momentum to Rajasthani cinema.
But the difficulties faced during film exhibition
were far greater than those faced during film production.
Producers’ interest in making Rajasthani films is gradually moving away from film production.
Sumit Kumawat.
Having previously worked as an assistant to K. C. Bokadia, he is a director of Rajasthani films.
Sumit Kumawat says that with the passage of time, Rajasthani films
should change their way of thinking and be made with new efforts.
So that audiences get to see something new and, over time, audience taste can be changed,
filmmakers should continue experimenting with new ideas.
The release of the book Life and Times of Maharaja Hanwant Singh.
By the Maharaja Man Singh Book Research Centre and the Mehrangarh Museum Trust.
On the occasion of the sixtieth coronation anniversary year of Maharaja Gaj Singh Ji.
Under the memorial lecture series of the late Maharaja Hanwant Singh.
Written by former Vice-Chancellor of Jai Narayan Vyas University, Professor L. S. Rathore.
The book Life and Times of Maharaja Hanwant Singh was released.
The program began with the offering of flowers to the images of Maa Sharada and the late Maharaja Hanwant Singh Ji.
At the program, former head of the Sociology Department of Jai Narayan Vyas University, Dr. Gopal Bhardwaj, said that Maharaja Hanwant Singh Ji had a unique identity not only in Jodhpur but across the entire world.
Despite his tall and broad physical stature, he had the tendency to take everyone along with him.
He said that the policies and words of Maharaja Hanwant Singh Ji are worth adopting in life.
Maharani Hemlata Raje said that once she went to London with Maharaja Gaj Singh Ji and the Rajmata.
At a lunch there, Lord Mountbatten spoke about the virtues of Maharaja Hanwant Singh Ji, saying that many of his own habits resembled those of Maharaja Hanwant Singh Ji.
The chief guest and speaker of the program, Professor Ravindra Kumar of Kurukshetra University, said that Maharaja Hanwant Singh Ji had the spirit of taking all thirty-six communities along with him.
Their ideals and thoughts were great.
While presiding over the program on this occasion, Maharaja Gaj Singh Ji expressed gratitude to Professor L. S. Rathore and said that this book would be translated into Hindi and Rajasthani.
On this occasion, the Director General of the Mehrangarh Museum Trust, Dr. Mahendra Singh Nagar, thanked the guests and the citizens.
The program was conducted by Bhanu Purohit.
Pious remembrance.
When a gathering of Mehdi Hasan was held in the Baradari of Umaid Bhawan.
Last month, on 13 June 2012, the world-renowned ghazal singer Mehdi Hasan passed away in the city of Karachi, Pakistan.
Mehdi Hasan was a native son of Rajasthan by birth.
He was born on 18 July 1927 in Loonan village of Jhunjhunu district.
Mehdi Hasan’s connection with Rajasthan was not limited to just this; it was here that he learned to weave ragas into ghazals with great simplicity from his father Azim Khan and his uncle Karim Khan.
Azim Khan, a master of Dhrupad singing, was at that time an artist at the Mandawa estate.
Just one year before Partition, Mehdi Hasan had gone to Pakistan with his father, but the separation from Shekhawati and the ripples of the scorching sandy dunes in summer became the identity of his voice.
Rajasthani folk tunes were in fact the real reason behind the magic in his music.
His connection with India always remained intact.
Thirteen years ago, he had come to Jodhpur in connection with a program.
On 10 April 1999, a Mehdi Hasan concert was held in the Baradari of Umaid Bhawan.
It was organized jointly by Swar Sudha and the Mehrangarh Museum Trust.
In that gathering, Mehdi Hasan touched the heights of ghazal singing,
which only Mehdi Hasan himself could achieve.
Originally from Rajasthan, when Mehdi Hasan began his melodic alap, it felt as if one were being drawn through the valleys of the Aravalli, hand in hand.
The resonance of his voice was no less than the waves shaped by the wind over the sandy dunes.
And the ghazal compositions woven into ragas felt like a spiritual voice rising from beside a shrine.
In raga Yaman, “Ranjish hi sahi, dil hi dukhane ke liye, aa.”
In raga Kirwani, “Dhuaan sa uthta hai.”
In raga Bhimpalasi, “Mohabbat karne wale kam na honge, teri mehfil mein, lekin hum na honge.”
In raga Maand, “Kesariya Balam aavo ni,” and in raga Pahadi Jhijhoti,
presenting “Zindagi mein sabhi pyaar kiya karte hain,” he made everyone his admirer.
For the music lovers of Jodhpur, that night became unforgettable.
Dhola Maru.
The dream came and passed, but sleep did not return to Marwar’s eyes.
When the eyes opened, there was darkness outside, and deep darkness within.
Rising, sitting, and lying down again, but the soul found no rest.
In the pond outside the village, the kurja bird cried.
Like the child of a kurja sleeping at home, with a long neck, the heart of the Marwari woman cried along with the kurja.
The Dhola seen in dreams, as soon as the threshold was crossed, felt to Maru as if he were the eternal beloved Dhola of many lifetimes.
The marriage that happened in childhood was not forgotten like a dream, but today, with the dream returning, Dhola stood clearly before her eyes.
A strange restlessness arose; there is someone dear, but she does not know him, she does not know him.
The dream came and awakened the entire being with a jolt.
By evening, the playful child who used to run along with her friends now, within a few hours, carried the weight of emotions and became a silent woman.
As the fingers of dreams moved over the strings of the heart, the melodies of love began to play, and wherever she looked or sat, only Dhola appeared.
In the pond, the kurjas kept crying, and Maru felt as if her companion had been separated; if that were not so, then why was there no sleep in her eyes, nor in mine.
Your state and mine are the same, but you have wings and feel like flying away; where are my wings, that I too could fly.
I saw that Marwari woman remained restless.
Playing and wandering with companions no longer felt good, there was no desire to work, and she no longer ran and clung around her mother’s neck as before.
The fine line of worry was clearly visible at the corner of her smiling eyes.
I understood a lot in a short time.
The worry was this.
The daughter had grown up, and there was no news from her in-laws.
Seeing this, King Pingal said that preparations should be made to send Maru to her in-laws’ home.
Yes, so many years have passed.
No news has come from Narwar.
If no one has come on their own, then we will send someone ourselves.
Send a message and call Dhola.
The marriage was arranged when Dhola was three years old, and when the girl grew up, she had already become mature.
What is the use of this delay?
The truth is this, Deodi, I have sent letters through many people to call Dhola; whoever went never returned, and my message never reached Dhola Ji.
Dhola’s marriage was with a Malwani woman; whoever goes by the path of Pugal, the Malwans kill him.
Pingal spoke in great sadness.
Deodi advised that now send some clever envoy, who will not arouse suspicion and will go directly to the beloved.
Let him go to Narwar, win over Dhola Ji with words and songs, and bring him back willingly.
Pingal approved of the advice.
He ordered a bard skilled in ragas and storytelling to go to Dhola.
Sending a maid to Maru, she called the bard to her side and began explaining the message to be conveyed to Dhola Ji: go and tell Dhola Ji that your Marwar has turned into burning coal, come and merge her ashes with yours.
There is no life left in this body like a bird in a cage.
Across the ridges, only her flame of burning remains.
Tell him this way, that the soul is with you, even if the body is kept far away.
If the bard meets Dhola personally, tell him surely that Maru’s eyes are waiting for his path, opening like a pearl shell, waiting for the raindrop of Swati.
Youth has reached the bend of the champa flower; come now and pluck the buds.
Remembering you, Maru has dried like the kair shrub.
Do not forget to tell Dhola Ji that the fire of separation is blazing; come and extinguish this wildfire.
Your beloved has withered like a lotus; rise like the sun.
Youth has become an ocean of milk; why do you not come and extract the gem.
With tears filling her eyes, breath choking, digging lines with her toes, Maru explained to the bard with a choked voice: join your hands in my name before Dhola Ji, he has forgotten me and sent no message at all.
Tell him, on what support should I live, on what support should I survive.
If he does not come by Phalgun, I will jump into the fire of Holi.
She composed a doha in Maru raga and gave it to the bard, telling him to sing it softly before Dhola Ji.
The bard took leave with respect, saying that if he lives he will bring Dhola Ji back, and if he dies he will remain abroad.
Clouds gathered, lightning flashed in the dark night, streaking, roaring, flashing in all directions, as if golden embroidery were being stitched on Indra’s black skirt.
Seeing Dhola sleeping on the terrace with lightning flashing, a melodic tune rose from the lower houses of the neighborhood.
In the cold night, Malhar raga spread through the gentle breeze along with the fine falling drops of rain.
Dhola lifted his hood high and began swaying to the raga like a serpent.
The singer said clearly in a sweet voice: Dhola of Narwar lanes, beloved of Poongal streets.
Dhola was startled, remembering that in childhood he was married to Marudhi.
He focused all his attention and began listening carefully.
A childhood marriage.
Dhola had forgotten it, as if a book had been opened and kept aside.
His eyes turned red, crying until his sight was blurred.
His beloved had been lying in a foreign land.
All night, the bard kept singing and Dhola kept listening.
The courtyard, gate, veranda, the entire house seemed filled with Marudhi’s message, and though Dhola lay on his bed, it felt as if he were rolling on hot ashes.
At daybreak, he called the villagers.
Where have you come from?
From Poongal, carrying a message from Marwar.
Waiting for Dhola, Marudhi has grown like the long-necked child of a swan.
She is longing to meet you, that golden-complexioned beloved.
Do not let false people’s words remove her from your heart.
Like a crane’s chick, Maru remembers you every moment.
Wringing her tear-soaked veil, blisters have formed on her delicate palms.
If you do not come by the first Teej of Sawan, she will die trembling at the sight of lightning.
The beauty and virtues of your Maru cannot be fully described.
One must have earned great merit in past lives to receive such a woman.
She is full of virtues, patient, gentle, and tender.
Fair like the waters of the Ganga, pure in body and mind.
She walks like an elephant, has teeth like diamonds, and lips like coral.
Your Maru has a waist like the Indus and eyebrows like the moon.
The face of a Marwari woman is brighter than the sun.
Through fine clothes her body shines as if gold is gleaming.
Dhola’s heart began to leap violently.
If the heart became a bird and the soul its wings, it would cross the forest and reach there at once.
His mind reached Maru, as if a hawk had been released from the fist.
Laughing-eyed, with a pearl necklace swaying on her chest, Malwan came smiling toward Dhola.
Seeing Dhola’s eyes, her lifted steps froze.
Why is this so?
What was yesterday is not so today.
A trident is marked on his forehead, and a nose ring is worn.
Something is wrong.
Why did the thought of Maru not come to him at all?
She sat beside him and began asking: today you are neither smiling nor speaking, have you become upset with me?
What is the worry?
Tell me then.
You are wise.
You understand everything.
Hiranakshi, if you permit and give your blessing, I will go abroad.
I will see foreign lands.
Dhola gave an excuse.
In whose house sweet melodies play and betel juice is fragrant,
who has a fine horse to ride and a beautiful woman at home, there is no need to go abroad.
Malvan replied.
Merchants will come here on their own.
You select carefully and buy a fine strong horse.
Dhola made many excuses, work here in Kutch, work there in Gujarat.
I will bring ornaments, I will bring garments, I will bring pearls.
Dhola Ji, you are restless, scratching the ground even with your nails.
Tell the truth clearly, what is in your heart.
Malvan’s doubt kept increasing.
The desire to meet Maru arose, and gradually Dhola revealed it.
Hearing this, Malvan suddenly collapsed in the courtyard, as if bitten by a snake.
She was fanned, sprinkled with water, and revived.
Dhola prepared to leave.
Then Malvan spoke.
In the monsoon season, one should not leave the house at all.
In such a time even a heron does not place its feet on the ground.
The cuckoo is calling, the koel is singing sweetly, the hills are turning green.
In such a season who goes out?
Neither beggars, nor thieves, nor servants leave their homes.
Rivers are in spate, clouds are pouring down, in these lovely days will I live without you?
The earth will look green, and your Malvan will turn pale without you.
How can I leave you and go away like these roaming clouds?
Stay through the entire monsoon.
I will wait till Dussehra, Dhola said with a sigh.
Indra is overflowing before the earth, clouds are hugging the peaks of the hills.
There Maru sits, stretching out her arms and giving me reproaches.
Days pass quickly.
The monsoon passed, Dussehra also passed.
Now Dhola prepared to go to Poongal; now the monsoon had been delayed because of you, winter has come, now I will go.
Beloved, wait.
These winter days are also not meant for travel.
Frost falls, even the horse must be covered.
In such times when pearls form in shells, deer conceive, and sharp northern winds blow, who leaves home?
In these days even snakes do not leave their holes.
The northern wind is blowing fiercely, waves of frost are moving.
It gives comfort to the united, but burns those in separation to ashes.
Malvan kept pleading.
Dhola mounted his ride.
Malvan, with brimming eyes, trembling, clung to his turban.
Dhola said, I will surely go.
You will fall asleep, I will leave quietly after you sleep.
Now Malvan did not sleep at all, she did not leave Dhola alone even for a moment.
Dhola had prepared a swift camel that could cover a hundred kos in a single day.
Malvan could not resist.
Thus fifteen days passed.
Malvan’s eyes became swollen; one day her eyelids finally closed from exhaustion.
Dhola called out to saddle the camel.
In an instant he mounted the camel and spurred it on.
The camel rose with a loud cry.
Hearing the camel’s call, Malvan startled; when she looked, Dhola was not beside her.
She rushed to the balcony and looked down, and saw Dhola going away riding the camel.
Seeing Malvan standing helpless in the balcony, it was as if lightning struck her.
She pulled at the camel’s reins, but in a moment the camel crossed the village boundary, and Malvan was left stunned.
Malvan kept crying out, someone stop Dhola Ji, someone stop Dhola Ji.
Dhola drove the camel hard and flew ahead.
Malvan began to wail.
Sometimes she lamented, sometimes cried aloud, sometimes cursed the camel, sometimes withered remembering him.
All four ends of her chunari were soaked with tears, all the kohl of her eyes had run.
She became pale, as if wrung like a wet cloth.
At the times Dhola used to pass, she went into the courtyard, grabbed fistfuls of dust marked by his footprints, and pressed them to her chest.
Dhola, filled with excitement, took the path toward Poongal.
Making many plans, forming grand intentions, striking the camel’s blanket, urging it on, crossing valleys, forests, and hills, he moved ahead.
On the way, atop the sand dunes, he saw a herdsman; thin bells were ringing on the camel’s neck, long tassels were hanging on both sides of the saddle, and the camel was moving as if a stream of water were flowing.
The rider’s head was shining brightly with zeal.
The herdsman said, is there some fair woman waiting at home, for whose sake you are running away in such harsh frost?
I am going to meet moon-like Marudi.
She is my companion, I am Marvan’s friend.
The herdsman smiled inwardly and spoke.
The camel’s reins slipped from Dhola’s hand.
Nearby, Umra’s grazing ground appeared.
Seeing Dhola going toward Poongal, the herdsman felt pity, looked closely, sighed, and said, Dhola Ji, for whom you are hurrying, Marvan has grown old, her hair has turned completely white.
Now what will you gain by going?
You have awakened very late.
Dhola’s heart trembled like a peepal leaf.
Neither could he step forward nor turn back.
Right there he held the camel’s reins and stood still.
What should I do now?
If I return, what face will I show to the people of the village?
He saw a man ahead.
With sadness Dhola asked, has Marvan of Poongal really grown old?
If you know, tell the truth plainly.
Have you lost your senses?
When you were married you were three years old, Marvan was one and a half; now you are a strong young man, how could she have grown old?
Dhola asked further questions.
The man paused for a moment and said, I have never seen or heard of a woman like Maru till today.
When she speaks in gatherings, it feels as if a veena is playing somewhere.
If she wears a silver ornament around her neck, then by the reflection of Maru’s body even that silver looks like gold.
Dhola immediately gave him a fistful of coins and urged the camel on.
He tightened his turban firmly and loosened the reins.
The camel began to race, talking to the winds.
By evening he reached Poongal.
Dhola met Marvan, and Marvan met Dhola.
It was as if after the scorching heat of Jeth in summer, the showers of Sawan fell on a creeper.
After four days, seeking leave, Dhola departed for home along with Marvan.
The camel was adorned.
Dhola Ji in front and Marvan behind mounted the camel.
Toward home the camel moved, Dhola urged it on, and the camel surged ahead.
Hearing this, Umra and Sumra realized Dhola was taking Marvan away alone.
They saw it as a very good opportunity to abduct Marvan.
In the middle of the way, they spread a carpet and sat down.
As soon as Dhola’s camel arrived, they stopped it with insistence, come, please come, accept our hospitality.
Many mute guests arrived.
Dhola left Marvan seated on the camel, himself sat on the carpet, and began accepting hospitality.
In the hearts of Umra and Sumra there was sin; seeing the opportunity, they planned to kill Dhola.
Marvan had no suspicion.
The bard was being given drink, Dhola Ji was taking the feast of intoxication.
The bard’s woman, from Poongal,
knew the sinful intent in the hearts of Umra and Sumra.
Quietly she went to Marvan’s ear and said, they plan to abduct you.
Run away with Dhola, otherwise he will be killed.
Marvan immediately gave the camel a kick.
As soon as it felt the kick, the camel rose and started running.
Dhola saw that the camel was fleeing.
Immediately he ran after the camel to catch it.
Marudi said, “It’s a trick—quickly climb onto the camel.”
Dhola had just placed his foot on the camel’s mounting strap to climb when the camel ran away.
Umro kept shouting, “Hey, hey.”
He immediately tried to mount the horse as well, but it was a black stallion.
The horse did not give him a chance to catch it.
The horse lagged behind.
Dhola and Marudi came home.
Dhola ji began living very happily with Marudi and Malvani.
O human.
Chandidas rightly said that—
O human, you are above everyone; there is no one above you.
Every scholar accepts this fact, that even upon a human raised like a tree
nature, society, and caste have an effect.
A human is essentially a division created by society.
Mutual interaction helps turn a human into a true human.
In the country where such mutual caste-based relations exist,
those relations themselves become the stream of human emotions.
But in these relations, this point must be kept in mind, that these mutual relations’
environment, and the way of life formed through that process,
and thoughts move parallel to each other.
Between these two matters, no cause-and-effect relationship can be firmly established.
This cannot be denied, that in Rajasthan too
there exist special kinds of mutual relations and a special historical background.
For this reason, in Rajasthan, the form of humans as it has been described
has been studied in many different ways.
In this article, I, only from a psychological perspective,
wish to observe the form of humans living in Rajasthan.
This thing has been observed many times that
when viewed through a psychological lens,
human relationships begin to appear in new ways.
From those experiences, many inferences can be drawn.
In the Gita, four types of knowledgeable humans are described.
The distressed, the inquisitive, the seeker of wealth, and the wise.
The form of humans found in Rajasthan does not allow the Gita’s classification to be directly applied.
The people of Rajasthan and its culture are of a special kind.
Here, humans are absorbed in themselves and also deeply immersed.
In the words of psychologist Freud, the ego of Rajasthani people is richly nourished by their desires.
If the four types of humans described in the Gita are interpreted from this angle, then they can apply to these people.
All the ideologies spread in Rajasthan, and all the sects,
are influenced and shaped from these four directions.
The influence of Advaita Vedanta that exists in the collective psyche of Rajasthan
has taken the form of Meera, Kabir, Raidas, Nanibai’s Mayro, and Sita Mata’s Mundri.
Through these, the truth of my assertion is fully validated.
Here, a person is absorbed only in their own thoughts and considers the entire world to be illusion.
They regard their own ego and the universe as one and the same thing.
On the land here, broadly speaking, the influence of formal religion has been relatively weak.
Here, natural religion has spread in a very unique and unconventional form.
Here, a voice has been heard.
“My old astrologer, when will I meet Ramiyo?”
The people of Rajasthan are deeply devoted to the path of devotion.
Because the means of livelihood here have not developed much,
the force of inner emotions on people here is very strong.
That person is primarily concerned with being absorbed in oneself.
They remain deeply engrossed within their own inner self.
This means that they remain confined only to themselves.
For this reason, they do not give proper attention to social relationships.
Especially toward those relationships that help make a person truly human.
Due to this reason, they have become ritualistic.
There is no unity between their actions and their thoughts.
Their behavior is not influenced by their thoughts.
The structure of society in Rajasthan is based on endogamous marriage.
Here, marital relations occur only within the same caste.
Because of these relations, interpersonal relationships are rigidly bound.
Even the father–son relationship here is not free from this rigidity.
Similarly rigid relationships also exist between elders and younger ones.
Wherever there is a father, a form of psychological conflict is also present.
Freud says that this conflict persists in the child.
And in different countries, its form appears differently.
In Western countries, the father–son relationship develops in such a way that
the father’s influence on the child is very strong.
But this does not apply to the people of Rajasthan.
Here, compared to the father, the mother’s influence on the son is greater.
In Rajasthan, child-rearing mostly takes place among women,
and this fact cannot be denied.
That in Rajasthan, a person remains childlike for a long time.
They are unable to come out of a self-absorbed state.
They remain absorbed within themselves.
After growing up, many forms of this attachment manifest.
In Marwar, the mutual expression seen in Iluji’s night awakenings exists because of this reason.
The way Iluji sits in the crowded market of Pali
with his legs spread out,
is itself a result of this self-absorbed state.
According to Freud, in Rajasthan,
the Oedipal conflict of children emerges unconsciously.
Because of this, the child’s rigidity toward the father remains in a different form.
In them, the fear of symbolic castration remains deeply ingrained.
Among Rajasthani women as well, this influence is clearly visible.
The changes that have come beneath the veil express this influence fully.
This influence is present even in families that have abandoned purdah.
Even there, girls are not free from this influence.
Again and again, attention keeps returning toward one’s own body.
In this, Freud’s assertion seems correct that the ego is fundamentally
determined by the body, and sometimes within the body,
the environment also plays a role.
Which remains closely connected to humans.
Due to these reasons, the temperament of Rajasthani people is intense.
They scatter emotionally over trivial matters.
Therefore, from a psychological point of view, the behavior of people here
is the behavior of fragmented individuals.
In Kautilya’s Arthashastra, the form of humans that has been described,
The people here have not been able to distance themselves from that legacy.
In Rajasthan, feudalism remained prevalent for nearly twelve centuries.
Its influence has also affected the people here and their culture.
The distinctions among Akha Teej, Lohri Teej, and Badi Teej are also found because of this.
Even if we do not discuss the internal pervasiveness and contradictions of culture here,
still a sense of superiority and a kind of arrogance has taken root among people.
In this way, no form of true humaneness remains among the people here.
That humaneness has been destroyed.
The attainment of their knowledge has become devoid of value.
Remaining detached from life, they keep creating their own knowledge.
Sometimes they do talk about pure knowledge,
but they do not reach the correct conclusion.
Today’s human is lonely, detached,
disconnected, weak, and frightened.
They are neither in a position to do good for themselves,
nor can they properly manage social relationships.
For them, their own existence has become meaningless.
They have not remained capable of reaching that stage where
they can comprehend ever-growing knowledge.
They are losing all those human capacities
which include utility, analysis, recognition, and evaluation.
Across the entire world, these abilities allow expansion and assessment.
In one word, they are not able to understand their own condition.
For them, a crisis-ridden state of existence has arisen.
Therefore, O human, you must change yourself.
As Western people say to you, O human,
like the goddess Saraswati, you must rise at twilight.
For you, the midnight has already passed.
You have moved beyond the stage of merely giving a roar.
You must understand that there is nothing greater than you
in this nature and the world.
Therefore, be alert, O human, be alert.
Awaken, O human, awaken, before your roots are destroyed.
Regional news.
All India Radio Jaipur Ajmer.
The central government has released one hundred thirty-six crore rupees for the National Food Security Mission.
To prevent fraud in cheque payments, the Reserve Bank of India has issued new guidelines.
In Barmer, work on the scheme to provide drinking water round the clock is ongoing, while due to low rainfall in the state, kharif sowing has been adversely affected at many places.
The central government has released eighteen hundred crore rupees to twenty-seven states, including Rajasthan, under the National Food Security Mission.
Rajasthan has been allotted one hundred thirty-five crore ninety-five lakh rupees.
With this amount, efforts will be intensified to increase pulse production in the state, and emphasis has been placed on increasing the production of rice and pulses.
Additionally, as required, focus will be given to improving agricultural techniques.
For road safety, the central government has provided assistance to states based on the number of vehicles plying on the roads.
This amount will be deposited in the Road Safety Fund.
From where it can be utilized as required.
The Ministry of Road Transport and Highways has sought information from state governments regarding the number of vehicles and the existing road safety mechanisms to decide the assistance amount.
The ministry will provide this assistance based on the recommendations of state and district road safety councils.
This amount will partly consist of funds collected under the Motor Vehicles Act by the states, and it will also be used to develop a road accident data management system.
Along with this, states have been instructed to use the road safety fund to purchase ambulances and cranes and to establish driver training institutes.
To prevent fraud in cheque payments, the Reserve Bank of India has issued several new guidelines.
Under these, for cheques of five lakh rupees or more, the clearing bank has been instructed to verify the cheque with the issuing party before clearing it.
For this purpose, banks will send information via SMS, and if no response is received from the concerned party within fifteen minutes, the cheque payment will be made.
In Barmer, under the Urban Infrastructure Development and Regulation Programme, work is underway to lay pipelines and build tanks at a cost of twenty-nine crore rupees.
According to our Barmer correspondent, once completed, drinking water will be available round the clock in Barmer.
A tribunal constituted under the chairmanship of Delhi High Court judge Justice V. K. Shali has upheld the Home Ministry’s decision to declare SIMI an unlawful organization.
The tribunal delivered its verdict in this matter on the first of August.
You may recall that on twenty-seventh December two thousand one, SIMI was first declared an unlawful organization.
In Rajasthan Public Service Commission’s two thousand six recruitment of third-grade teachers, Chief Minister Ashok Gehlot has granted fresh relief to four hundred sixty-two candidates who did not get jobs.
This benefit will be given to those candidates who appeared for the B.Ed examination from Jeevaji University but were not selected because the results were not declared by the stipulated date.
The government is seriously considering a scheme to build resting facilities for litigants in courts across the state.
The Minister for Law, Justice, and Urban Development, Shanti Dhariwal, said this today at the oath-taking ceremony of the Advocates’ Council in Bundi.
Mr. Dhariwal also inaugurated the pipeline scheme under the Urban Infrastructure Development Project to supply water from the Mangli River to Bundi city.
On this occasion, he said that so far sixteen crore twenty-three lakh rupees have been spent on the drinking water scheme for Bundi.
British MP Deb Jarvis today reviewed various health schemes in Jaipur and in Rupnagar of Ajmer district.
Praising the Chief Minister’s Free Medicine Scheme and the Janani Suraksha Yojana as very useful, she said that these would increase institutional deliveries and reduce maternal and infant mortality rates.
Ms. Jarvis emphasized the need to eliminate malnutrition among children.
Earlier, the British MP met Health Minister Imaduddin Ahmed Khan and also visited a free medicine distribution center.
Vedanta Group’s Hindustan Zinc Company is conducting artificial rainfall through cloud seeding technology in the districts of Udaipur, Chittorgarh, and Rajsamand in the state.
For this purpose, the company has arranged a special aircraft at Maharana Pratap Airport in Udaipur.
For this, approval has been obtained from the administration and the concerned departments.
As soon as clouds form, this aircraft will take off and spray common salt on moisture-laden clouds, causing the salt to absorb moisture particles and convert them into small droplets.
Our Udaipur correspondent said that the estimated expenditure on this project is between fifteen and twenty crore rupees.
Due to the lack of monsoon activity in the state, the situation has become a cause for concern.
The Meteorological Department has expressed hope for rainfall at some places.
However, except for two millimeters of rainfall in Peepalda of Kota district, Shahabad of Baran district, Salumber of Udaipur district, and Lasadiya in Dungarpur, Banswara, and Udaipur districts, the entire state remains dry over the last twenty-four hours.
So far this year, only nineteen out of seven hundred twenty-four dams in the state have filled, and normal rainfall has occurred only in six districts—Dholpur, Karauli, Baran, Jhalawar, Dungarpur, and Banswara.
Due to the weak monsoon, kharif sowing has also been affected in the state, and compared to the target of one hundred fifty lakh hectares, sowing has been done only in seventy lakh hectares.
Considering the drought situation, the state government has decided to continue relief work until fifteenth August in sixty villages of Bikaner, Bhilwara, and Jaisalmer districts.
Yesterday, due to heavy rainfall in Jodhpur district of Rajasthan, there has been a significant drop in temperature.
Now a summary of other news received from districts.
In Dholpur today, there is news of two persons stealing two lakh rupees from a customer at a Bank of Baroda branch.
In Tonk district, near Banthali, a collision between a roadways bus and a motorcycle resulted in the death of a young man and serious injuries to a young woman.
Success has been achieved in cultivating colored capsicum.
For its irrigation as well, a unique technique has been adopted.
A report by B. C. Jitendra Singh Poonia.
At the London Olympics, Rajasthan athlete Krishna Poonia has reached the final of the women’s discus throw event.
The final competition will be held tonight at twelve o’clock.
A strong medal contender from India, Poonia ranked eighth in the qualifying round.
The Commonwealth Games gold medalist Poonia threw the discus sixty-three point five four meters and stood fifth in her group.
With this, she has become the sixth Indian athlete to secure a place in an Olympic final.
Evening at the water ghat.
All day long, the earth is blazing like a potter’s kiln.
From the holes of all ten directions, flames keep emerging, filling every particle of the sky with unbearable heat.
Fierce hot winds, like thousands of raging demons, race across the flat chest of the burning earth, laughing and roaring wildly.
They know no obstacles on the road, no sense of direction, no pause even for a moment, only stumbling over high and low sand dunes, falling and rising, and with their countless fists flinging heavy mounds of sand into the sky, they perform a frenzied dance of destruction.
Wherever signs of life appear, they lick them again and again with their red tongues and make every corner of the world echo with their powerful laughter.
Those who have life and seek refuge to hide their breath have concealed themselves in courtyards, walls, and corners, spending the day panting.
The roaring storm keeps banging forcefully on the closed doors of houses, making the people inside realize the outside world, and then, disappointed, beating its chest, it turns back.
All day long, a dance of destruction has taken place on the chest of creation.
Fire has rained from the sky, and flames have risen from the earth upward.
But now the third quarter of the day is slowly passing.
The hot winds, whose eyes roamed madly all day, now exhausted, lie down under the slanting shadow of the dunes.
Occasionally, warm breaths still reach here.
The birds leave the walls and descend below.
The twisted neem tree in front of my house, which all day hissed in anger at the rampage of the hot winds, now stands silently like an ascetic, lifting its head toward the free sky.
The shadow of the neem tree lies long, touching the high parapet of the well beside it and stretching up to my veranda.
I sit under the shade of the neem tree in front of the veranda, holding my hookah.
Nature lies quiet and still, as if after rising from a long illness, it has returned once again and, looking around,
stands silently, lonely, and indifferent.
On the high parapet of the well, the cooing of pigeons has begun.
Birds have started chirping.
The music of life and consciousness has begun, and I lie on my cot, gazing at the open sky.
I have reached the highest sky of imagination.
But my eyes do not close.
As I lie there watching, a bullock cart loaded with thick logs creaks along, the driver coming behind, urging his bullocks with calls.
The melodious tinkling of the small brass bells hanging from the necks of the bullocks is a magical, soothing music of life.
After a while, it seems as if something has stopped, but the knocking sound echoes from the village, strikes the door of the horizon, and returns again—the deep voice of the cart driver.
So, in the dung of the blackened earth, there is the melody of strength and the call of vigor.
Listening to it, in every house the jingling of the hard anklets of water-carrying women resounds.
Like every day, today too the water carriers have arrived.
New brides have arrived carrying the new light of youth.
From beneath the swirling ghaghras around their feet up to their ankles, silver anklets hang, and the sweet jingling of anklets and bells rises, while the flashing toe-rings make the young men of the village sitting under the neem tree sparkle with delight.
Along with the new brides have come the older, experienced daughters-in-law, whose youthful charm has faded, but whose unbroken rule still prevails inside the household.
They make up for the loss of youthful beauty with fine jewelry and clothes.
The veil of the new brides rests just above their noses.
Even when pulled down repeatedly, the stubborn veil slips back up again.
In the eyes shining behind those veils is a sharp sparkle that pierces straight through hearts.
The market for the beauty of the elder daughters-in-law has now ended.
To compensate for the loss of beauty, today they lower their eyelids and establish an ideal of modesty and restraint.
Along with these daughters-in-law and young girls in blooming youth, an occasional mother-in-law also arrives.
Her bent waist bends even more under the weight of the water pot as she walks.
The old woman, spreading a smile of affection over her dry lips, requests the agile young girl to lift the pot for her, but as usual, disappointed, she mutters and walks on with the pot resting on her hip.
Hearing her muttering, the suppressed laughter and giggles of the daughters-in-law and girls tinkle and spread through the air, startling everyone.
Thus the water-carrying women, shedding the outer shell of beauty, create an extraordinary beauty in the Rajasthani evening.
As they climb up and down the steps of the well, the clinking of heavy ornaments makes all ten directions resound, and listening to the roaring hum of the well echoing over the steps, one becomes aware of the cycle of joy and sorrow.
But the cart driver, absorbed in his task, remains engaged with an unchanging mind in filling and emptying.
At home, beauty and appearance, youth and knowledge, life and renunciation present a strange combination to be seen.
In the glow of the setting sun, when the entire surrounding world turns vermilion, the bleating of sheep and goats come to drink water, the lowing of cattle echoes in the sky, dust rises from their feet and spreads colorfully in the air, and the driver’s call grows louder and louder—while listening to the music of life at the water ghat, my eyes slowly close.
Slowly, from the eastern direction of the sky, a soft, gentle darkness advances, swallowing daylight and consciousness.
The coming and going of the water carriers stops, the sound of the cart gradually fades away, and the bullocks with sweetly tinkling bells slowly disappear into the darkness ahead of the driver.
While repeatedly reflecting on the magnificent form of life and its unbroken music, I unknowingly reach the world of dreams, without realizing it.
The Rajasthani evening at the water ghat is truly extraordinary.
From the courtyard of new poetry.
A new thing appears beautiful to everyone.
Man demands novelty even at the cost of breaking things.
Breaking things is a flawed act and of no real use.
From the time of our country’s independence until today, across the entire nation,
countless new writers, poets, and storytellers have emerged as pioneers of new literature.
While reflecting on new poetry in this essay, this question naturally arises—
that Rajasthani writers have not been able to keep pace for long with the meaningful current of the new movement.
A voice that breaks the narrow walls of religion, caste, color, and class, rising from the earth and resonating across the sky.
The definition of new poetry.
In the field of poetry, new rules, forms, techniques, and simple direct experiments of free verse,
with a strong voice of humanity, human dignity, and freedom amid the conflicts between man and society.
These experiments can occur only on a social level, not at an individual level.
When these arise from the sharp tip of the new poet’s pen and begin forming lines of the age on paper,
those who read them feel that this poetry expresses the joys and sorrows of life, society, man, and humanity, and is impactful.
Those who listen say that this novelty is a living, vibrant poetic note.
Discerning critics, after judging its emotion and depth, say that the composition is genuine.
When there is no mixture and it is a fresh creation, a new discovery, only then do we call a work new poetry.
In this sense, new poetry is not written in the artificial language of its scholars.
Whoever can grasp its essence grasps the life and faith of millions of people.
A poet who maintains distance from this essence, in my view, cannot be better than a dead man.
By the word faith, I mean a sense of moral responsibility.
Independently speaking, it is true that poetry is poetry itself, neither new nor old.
Moment by moment, what is new becomes old.
But today the call of the new is very strong.
The emotional ground of new poetry.
New poetry stands on the foundation of experimentalism.
Today, in our country’s literary field, especially in Hindi, four poetic streams are active.
One is new poetry or experimentalism.
Second is traditionalism, the old stream.
Third is progressivism or communism.
Fourth is synthesis and coordination.
These four poetic streams have different paths and different arenas.
Even the camp of new poetry or experimentalism cannot be said to have a single form.
Within it too are many schools—Nalini Vimotion Sharma, Kesharikumar, and Naresh Mehta among them.
A mixed khichdi of one-and-a-half measures is cooked differently.
Without clearly understanding the emotional foundation of new poetry, we cannot move forward.
Therefore, first it is necessary to reflect upon this.
The emotional ground of new poetry means the foundation of new poetry.
While explaining this, the Hindi poet Sumitranandan Pant writes in the introduction to new poetry.
New poetry lifts human emotion with full force from the shadowy broken ground, like a beating cradle.
Life has set out to swim amid the turbulent waves of the ocean.
Where, with the courage to endure joy and sorrow, hope and despair,
it can face the shocks and upheavals of the life of the age.
Freed from personal pain, it becomes acquainted with the experiences of society’s suffering.
New poetry, inspired by universal human rights, becomes highly motivated and energized.
Flourishing and, in today’s rapidly changing age-pattern, through the signals of free verse,
combining fast and slow rhythms, it is creating a new emotional ground for modern humanity.
When a child learns to speak, even its lisping speech sounds very beautiful.
We too smile at that new speech; this is exactly the nature of new poetry.
Old children and childlike elders, both kinds of poets, belong to this camp.
These people find speaking easy, writing confusing, and publishing loudly celebrated.
The poets of new poetry have so far preserved their call in the three Tar Saptaks.
These people call themselves experimentalists in the field of poetry.
But they are better recognized by the name of explorers of searching paths.
The characteristics of new poetry.
It portrays social reality and emotion.
In the context of domestic events of life, it evaluates emotional beauty.
Emphasis on new word-planning, stylistic brilliance, new flashes of imagery, and new formations of simile, metaphor, and symbolism.
Awakening of contemporary consciousness by freeing oneself from decayed traditions and old symbols.
Viewing and examining nature from all sides.
New discovery of human nature and new devotion in the science of man.
Expressing the unspoken aspects of life through deep sensitivity of emotions.
Upholding human power, freedom, and self-determination.
Grasping light from the edge of darkness, happiness from the edge of sorrow.
The new poet grasps existence from the edge of ego, and faith from the edge of doubt.
In this way, he neither drowns so deeply in the ocean of emotion that he loses life itself.
Nor is it right that he stands permanently atop the peak of intellect.
New poetry opposes blind followers of fixed lines.
New poetry opposes people who wander in the storms of ideologies and are nurtured in the shadows of foreign lands.
New poetry accepts Western influence, but on the foundation of Indian values and ideals.
In today’s world, deliberately closing one’s eyes and creating darkness may be possible.
In every age, the characteristics of each literature have been described.
One idea gradually becomes established.
A new idea is opposed.
In this context, when we have already reflected on the characteristics of new poetry,
it seems forcefully correct that its critics say something like this.
Those who consider criticism as abuse and nonsense are regarded as unworthy of the temple of literature.
I wish to draw your attention with one more request.
That after seeing both sides, we should not jump to conclusions.
Keeping this in mind, you will read sharp and frank criticism of new poetry.
This is my belief.
New poetry amid criticism.
The search for living emotion and soul in creation has gone very far, and meeting it has become difficult.
Complete emptiness of inner feeling and deep experience.
Chanting of ideology, and pride in place of self-respect.
A dense cloud of boredom, disbelief, sexual anger, impulse, complexity, and defeatist frustration appears spread out.
Incomplete imagery, limping similes, false ornamentation, in the rush of new language.
Such as words formed like “wind-feeling,” “evening-feeling,” “pain-feeling,” “sense-feeling,” and “ridiculous.”
Severe confusion between object and subject, subject and object.
Word, meaning, and rhythm—all three show many forms through mutual rupture.
There is no concern for the spirit of the age, social consciousness, or ideals.
Petty humanism, hollow humanitarianism, and inability to integrate into society.
In this “you versus me” quarrel, what is achieved other than breaking pots and jaggery.
In compositions, the subtle grasp of poetic vitality and lyrical touch is missing.
And the hollowness of basic vision and thought is clearly visible.
The harmony of emotion and language, which critics call aesthetic delight, is found only here and there in this poetry.
The distribution of borrowed ideas from the outer world has spread greatly in this poetry, which is unnational in character.
The aesthetic sense, commitment, obstinacy, and value-confusion of new poetry are tightly held by the forceps of artificial values.
New names, new coinages, and breaking rigid literary conventions are the fruits of this poetry’s influence.
The life expressed in the creations of new poetry and its contemporary tendencies reveal the difference in its condition.
A contradiction is visible between what poets say and what they do.
This poetry, remaining isolated from the masses, has not yet been able to fully spread its light.
The past and future of new poetry.
At present, new poetry is passing through a phase of transition.
Various kinds of experiments and various kinds of ideological awareness are spreading within its scope.
On one side, it bends toward blind traditional beliefs.
On the other side, in its courtyard, the hungry generation and naked poets,
along with noisy chaos and reckless indulgences, are seen rising clearly.
What is regrettable is this very fact, that the poet of new poetry, whose poems and songs describe
the virtues and flaws of life and society,
maintains a very wide distance from real life.
He speaks of the hungry generation, yet indulges in luxury in coffee houses and hotels.
He speaks of nakedness, crude sexuality, and women sitting inside homes, and if someone even raises an eye toward daughters-in-law,
then a single deity rises with drawn swords.
This seems self-contradictory.
Many poets have badly distorted the subject matter itself.
They all appear to be playing the game of blind men wrestling.
On the nineteenth page of the Third Saptak, it has been clearly stated,
that many poems written in the name of new poetry clearly lack substance.
Treating the subject itself as substance, it appears like a confused and entangled picture.
Here it must be accepted that among new poets, such cases are not few.
Those who made the mistake of treating the subject as substance did so repeatedly, and in this way became misguided themselves.
At the same time, they also became a cause for spreading confusion among readers about new poetry.
Regarding lyricism and intellectual experimentation in poetry, on the fifty-third page of Kavya Dhara, Dr. Nagendra has made a very balanced statement.
That language is a social instrument.
Its meaningfulness lies in making people’s viewpoints clear to society.
There is hunger in society, and there is a human who suffers hunger.
The front and back of these two fans are what new poetry is seeing today.
What is needed is caution.
Work cannot be accomplished by spinning wheels alone.
If there are flowers, there are thorns; if there are waves, there is collision; if there is rain, there is storm.
Joy and sorrow and many such good and bad things we see, endure, and experience; if someone listens, we speak, otherwise we keep speaking to ourselves.
I consider new poetry to be like a football.
Filled tightly with air, it is very light, but it retains strong force.
It rises high, touches the sky, and on the ground makes many run.
It does not belong to one side; it belongs to the players.
It keeps moving toward both the winning and the losing teams.
This was merely a matter of metaphor.
The real fact is that even after independence, the poor people of the country are still deeply distressed.
Among ordinary, middle-path people, your and my brothers and sisters themselves are those poets.
Our way of seeing, understanding, writing, thinking, reflecting, and perceiving should rely much more on honesty and much less on fame.
I say here that the life those people live is the real life.
Amid the glitter and show of cities like Delhi, Calcutta, Bombay, Jaipur, and Chandigarh,
they have maintained such restraint
that apart from placing their own voice before the people, they do nothing beyond that.
This is the true religion of humanity.
In the history of the last thousand years, poets have never had this much freedom,
and at the same time, such opportunities to witness and experience scarcity, war, unemployment, disease, poverty, and political upheaval
have never been available before.
At the speed with which the entire world is being gathered beneath our feet,
and as the steady pace of science continues to increase,
the turmoil created everywhere today by factories, schemes, and ever-new technologies,
how can any artist remain untouched in the sphere of influence?
Yes, keep separating the grain from the husk.
To explain this matter, I present one thought.
Goswami Tulsidas was a new poet of his time.
The poetic courage he expressed in the folk language was never accepted by the established authorities of that era.
But after living in darkness for thirty years, Tulsidas was embraced by the people.
That brilliance still shines before your and my eyes.
New poetry carries the life of the age.
New poetry will not bloom and flourish unless it receives the blessing of becoming the voice of the people.
Unbroken darkness lies ahead.
The person who understands and searches for the path will surely reach the destination one day.
New poetry must hear the call of the age and make the whole world hear it.
If new poetry can establish a true harmony between life and living people, then this stream will become the people’s own.
Its deep and strong roots will surely take hold.
Poetry is the voice that teaches the completeness of our life.
The deep-rooted truths of tradition and values cannot be forgotten.
The cultures of the lands of Freud, Jung, Adler, Marx, Engels, and Ginsberg, and of our own soil,
and the progressive streams—today the gap between them in life-currents is like that of past ages.
While accepting good traditions and strong counter-arguments, bias should not be maintained.
The Sanskrit poet Rajshekhar, in the treatise Kavya Mimamsa, counted eight mothers of poetry.
Health, talent, practice, devotion, scholarship, wide learning,
strength of memory, and humility—these eight factors today,
when viewed from a new perspective, allow us to sift out the core elements of new poetry.
The wave of new poetry is the demand of the times.
No language can escape this.
The history of the Rajasthani language has always preserved the brightness of change.
It can be hoped that the attention of Rajasthani writers and poets toward literature
will now turn much more swiftly toward this new stream.
Many paths have already been adopted.
Many styles of movement are being practiced.
The only point worth attention is that we must raise our pen upon the living aspects of public life
by awakening the inspiration of rural consciousness rooted in the culture and heritage of our language,
from which older writers remained far removed.
With respect to time and place, through new styles, craft, figurative formulation, image planning,
harmonization of taste, unity of word, meaning, and rhythm, and through new thought and reflection,
the doors of a new era will open in Rajasthani literature.
This moment of waiting for the blossoming dawn of laughing, joyful life is the Brahma Muhurta—highly auspicious and celebratory.
How can speaking the truth ever be harmful?
The world beats the drum of truth, yet when one speaks the truth, what harm occurs?
The work of falsehood only adorns falsehood itself.
Where speaking the truth breaks one’s head and lifelong enmity settles in, there falsehood easily accomplishes tasks.
Falsehood is such an infallible weapon that it stands ready at every moment.
Where truth’s ox-cart gets stuck and its wheel jams, there falsehood’s flying ship vanishes in a blink before the eyes.
Yet from ancient times till today, countless people—great and small—have been cut down, but they kept blowing the conch of truth.
The wonder is that those whose livelihood runs on falsehood have dyed their lives in falsehood.
And even those who cannot speak the truth themselves still swear by truth—there is no penance equal to truth, no sin equal to falsehood.
You may think the writer’s mind seems disturbed.
Those who seat themselves in this flying craft of falsehood will smash those innocent ones mercilessly.
My innocent ones have no need to fear.
Like one who buys a train ticket and then stretches out fearlessly, trusting that when sleep breaks, they will reach the destined platform,
in the same way, I too will disembark at my destined place.
What kind of falsehood is this that sticks like a thorn?
Again, one day, the place of truth will surely be reached.
The scriptures say: Yato dharmas tato jayah—where there is righteousness, there is victory.
This is the final verse of the Gita.
“Where Yogeshwar Krishna is, where Arjuna the archer stands, where steadfast morality and victory reside—there prosperity, success, and justice are assured.”
Its Rajasthani translation was done by Vishwanathji Vimlesh.
Where Yogeshwar Lord Krishna stands, where Arjuna the bow-bearer is present, steadfast justice and victory are certain—this is my belief.
People say the poor Pandavas remained righteous, and in the end victory was theirs.
Anyone with even slight knowledge of the Mahabharata
knows that Lord Krishna had vowed not to wield weapons.
But when he saw the Pandava forces being pierced like a sieve by Bhishma’s sharp arrows,
he did not hesitate to abandon his vow to uphold truth.
He lifted a chariot wheel in his hand and charged toward Bhishma.
And at that moment, Bhishma’s burning arrows found relief in his chest.
Krishna was clever, a master strategist—let that matter rest.
Alright, let it rest.
When Dharmaraj Yudhishthira saw Guru Dronacharya destroying the Pandavas,
all warriors—rathis, maharathis, and atirathis—began to hide,
heads began to droop, and with Krishna’s assurances, Arjuna’s victory plans
started dissolving into dust.
At that moment realization dawned that if one clings stubbornly to truth, the Pandavas were doomed.
Defeat was certain, along with disgrace.
People say he remained righteous, but in the end he suffered the consequences of his own actions.
Now whose infallible weapon came to mind?
But the man who always speaks falsehood, once it comes out from his own head, its infallibility is instantly destroyed.
For this reason it was made to be said through Dharmaraj Yudhishthira.
Ashwatthama is dead, but not a man, it is the elephant.
Why so, why is it not so?
Drona’s son Ashwatthama is considered immortal, and the one who died that day was only an elephant bearing that name.
But if the shelter of falsehood had not been taken, then Dronacharya’s death
how would it have happened, and who would have defeated the living Kaurava army?
Who would get entangled in the tangles of the Puranas?
This is the true matter.
Accept it as history.
The Sun of Mewar, Maharana Pratap Singh, is today regarded as the pride of all India.
But when Raja Man Singh came to his house and invited him to dine together from the same plate,
and called the Maharana for that, then he did not consider it right to speak the truth.
In whose refuge did he go?
He did not say this, Man Singh,
that your daughter has relations with Muslims, therefore I will not dine with you.
The Rana said, you eat, my stomach is aching.
When the British came to India at Surat,
they certainly did not say that we have come here to rule.
If they had said so, the people of that time would have struck them with sandals.
For this reason the British said,
we only want to trade with India.
They traded in such a way that they took control over the country, and India became enslaved.
Foolish talks.
Dragged and worn-out arguments.
It is the truth.
Remember it.
“Hindi–Chinese brotherhood.”
It became a powerful slogan.
India’s innocent brothers accepted it as true.
But the cunning Chinese said, let us keep chanting this slogan falsely again and again.
And side by side, let us keep our actions going on quietly.
China today is sitting after establishing control on India’s open land.
Till now the matter has not come to a complete end.
If guests place their hand on their own heart, then they themselves will admit how much work falsehood has accomplished for us.
But if the writer wants to take evidence from someone, then take it, there is no objection.
On the second date, a certain gentleman came to me, whom I know in many ways.
As soon as he came, impatient and stubborn, showing attitude, he said, I need ten rupees, immediately.
I know this very well that the rupees once given will never come back.
And if ever one says that they are there but I will not give, then enmity arises.
Even then I committed this foolishness, that I said, the rupees are there, but I will not give.
The result was that the gentleman now considers me his enemy till today.
The day after tomorrow there was a wedding at Advocate Sahib’s house.
Preparations were made, and I went to Dr. Vyas to ask for furniture.
The doctor allows even his children to sit on this decorative furniture only occasionally.
At the wedding, sharbat, rabri, goat’s legs, paan spit, everything is openly available.
Furniture that has been carefully preserved for so many years,
will come back ruined after use.
And if any chair’s leg or thread breaks, then it has to be repaired from home, for which
money will hardly be reimbursed by Advocate Sahib.
Thinking this, the doctor went inside the room.
Slowly he placed the furniture inside the room and locked it.
He took the keys, then making an excuse told Advocate Sahib that Munni’s mother says the room key has been lost for two days.
The lock is also of Godrej; if it were some cheap lock, it could have been broken or forced.
When the key is found, we will ourselves send it.
You please have the list written.
See the miracle of falsehood.
The furniture was not given, and the reputation was also preserved.
There is no need to give many such examples, because on occasion all of us
to some extent or the other, become Dr. Vyas.
And if we do not become so, then in this world it is not just difficult to survive, it becomes impossible.
But even then this point is worth attention, that the man who eats poison pills,
in his body the poison does not spread in the same way.
Similarly, those people who always speak lies, their lies become ineffective.
If one wants to take advantage of the infallible weapon of falsehood, then one must choose the right occasion to use it.
If you develop the habit of speaking lies every day,
then there will be no one lighter than you in this world.
And if at some critical moment you ever use it, then this infallible weapon will work.
Even now if my point has not reached you,
then my only advice to you is that you become the truth-following Harishchandra.
The human birth.
Human birth is not attained just like that.
Among countless life-forms, from crawling insects to huge elephants, human life is the highest on this earth.
While shaping the human, it feels as if even the craftsmanship of the Creator got exhausted.
While creating this image, the creator himself seems to have become the image.
The human seems like the flower of heaven, like the Creator’s own inner call.
Like the waves of the Ganga, or like the energy of the directions.
Like the fragrance of sandalwood.
Clad in the attire of forest flowers, with the musk of the deer’s breath, and the thirst of the rain-bird absorbed, dressed in the essence of soil.
In the human form, it is as if the auspicious resolve of creation became manifest.
As if the penance of the primal yogi Shiva took form, as if the earth itself was adorned.
When a human was born, it was as if God himself descended into the lap of the earth.
The moment a human was born, birds chirped joyfully and sparrows sang auspicious songs.
Sunrays spread their light, scattering brightness into the courtyard.
Lotus petals scattered pearls of dew.
Mango blossoms were married to the bees.
Spring blossomed forth.
The sky became luminous.
Human birth is the wealth of this earth, a priceless gem.
This gem-like wealth was accepted joyfully into the lap of life’s Yashoda.
The barren earth attained motherhood and bloomed with fulfillment.
Love-filled, longing Meera danced in ecstasy, her head bowed in blissful pride.
Even the innocent village cowherd girls stepped two steps ahead of palace-born Meeras and danced freely.
They too danced with a bowl of buttermilk and attained the supreme fruit of life.
But alas, this precious gem of human life, through countless births, was squandered meaninglessly.
A diamond was mistaken for broken glass.
Deceived, one suffered loss.
The jewel trader’s priceless diamond was sold for a cowrie shell by butcher-like fate, trading away humanity.
The jeweler’s son dirtied his hands in coal brokerage.
Great gods, men, sages, and scholars, though wrapped in the cloak of human birth, soiled it nonetheless.
Only a true servant of Lord Ram, with great effort, wore it and kept it as it was—what then happened?
Seeing the plight of humanity, the earth wept, and the Creator grew sorrowful.
Why has this condition of human birth arisen?
Why does a worm infest a flower?
Why does soot blacken a lamp’s flame, why does wildfire blaze in forests?
The pure stream that bursts forth like nectar at Gangotri,
why does it later mix with the ocean and turn salty?
Who breaks the toy while playing?
No one knows its name.
A two-letter name—Maya—which gathers both this world and the other world into its grip and wraps all human deeds and faiths.
That which makes everyone dance, deludes them, and destroys knowledge and meditation.
Before which even great ascetics and the virtuous cannot cross over.
What is this Maya?
Just an illusion.
Like a scarecrow placed to drive birds away from Ram’s fields.
Like a single peg supporting a taut tambura string.
Or is it some complete, solid thing whose form and color are visible in living beings?
Maya’s colors are unfathomable, its forms infinite.
Some see it as a flower blooming without fruit, some perceive it as a mirage.
Some mistake the illusion of silver in a shell itself as Maya.
Some fear it in the terrifying form of death, others are enticed and deluded by it as desire.
Maya has a thousand names.
She becomes Indra’s consort Indrani, and Brahma’s consort Brahmani.
Greed, attachment, deceit, hypocrisy, falsehood—Maya, the formidable force, conquers the world.
Even a devotee like Tulsidas falters, then takes refuge in the name of Ram.
So what indeed is this Maya?
Who can understand such profound matters?
Who has the time to untangle these knots of thought?
Here, even cows like the Gita and Gayatri are not spared from being milked dry.
Who then will churn the buttermilk?
So then understand this: that which entangles you itself and does not let others escape, that alone is Maya.
That which itself consumes everything but does not let others partake, that alone is Maya.
That which diverts a human from the righteous path and drives him onto a crooked one, that alone is Maya.
Why do worms infest a flower?
Because filth lies at its roots.
Earnings born of filth may let a flower bloom and blossom,
it may smile, but it cannot escape the worms of desire and the termites of worry; that very filth is called Maya.
Fire easily ignites in a bamboo grove.
Forgetting their own lineage, provoked by the whisper of passing wind, with a single spark they fight and die among themselves.
Striking against the friction of anger and jealousy, they perish.
The entire lineage of the Kauravas and Yadavas was burnt to the roots by that single spark, by that single fire.
What chance do others have?
So this very tendency is called Maya.
A lamp burns and gives light, that is true.
But who is remembered?
The lamp burns on the oil of affection, but the affection belongs to another.
In the oil-press the poor sesame is crushed and ground, donating the essence of oil.
The wick too is made of cotton.
So light that shines by the sacrifice of others must inevitably gather soot.
Deceit always stains sacrifice.
Thus deceit itself is called Maya.
The sacred river Bhagirathi descended from the divine realm.
The dazzling whiteness of snowy peaks pricked the eyes with truth.
Seeing greenery below, it then began to meander.
It forgot the lofty place, the divine abode.
The water turned muddy, and salt mixed into it.
It is rightly so: the water of life remains steady only at its source.
When it falls downward, the water becomes impure.
Thus downfall itself is called Maya.
Maya deceives by assuming an alluring form.
It catches birds flying after shadows.
The shadow-grasping demon Surasa, the mother of serpents, always tried to swallow Hanuman by tearing open her mouth.
She came according to the ordained custom; in this there was no injustice.
Surasa, meaning the mother of delightful tastes, earthly attachment, who in the form of various objects and desires is the progenitor of serpents.
Always humble yet firm, Hanuman overcame her playfully.
But firmness and determination, taking a more terrifying form with double force, becomes uncontrollable.
If it could be controlled, it would not be the true Hanuman.
Breaking the enchanting attachment of household life, the one who took a leap crossed the ocean.
He attained the title of the best among men, Hanuman.
But the one who remained on this side stayed merely a monkey.
Thus attachment to home and family that obstructs effort and valor is called Maya.
But in this way the forms of Maya cannot be fully counted.
Where should one begin listing them?
Tell some straightforward remedy to reform human life.
So then listen: the foundation of all human activity is this—
thinking, speaking, and doing.
The cart of human life has two wheels: speech and action.
Thinking is its axle; if the axle and the two wheels are sound, the cart moves smoothly.
Thinking is the axle.
The axle must remain firm, steady, and unshakable.
Restlessness of mind is not a sign of courage.
Keep unwavering faith in God and make firm resolve.
One with firm resolve remains fearless.
When resolve is firm, the mind is fearless; it does not waver or tremble; fate’s numbers then diminish, misfortune lessens.
One who thinks and reflects before acting is pure.
The wise one builds the embankment before the water arrives.
Think and then act, but never act and then think.
One who thinks is noble, one who acts then thinks is foolish; thinking brings light to the face, acting without thought brings dust.
When the axle of thinking remains right, the two wheels of speech and action run properly; that is harmony.
A wealthy man once said to a saint.
Keep your actions moving, and wealth will keep doubling day by day.
The merchant set the business in motion.
The craftsmen got to work.
If the method of earning is not properly arranged, the functioning of the business comes to a halt.
This is the very secret hidden in this mantra.
Speech is also necessary.
Action alone is mute, and speech alone is lame.
And without thought, both are blind.
When all three come together, one succeeds.
Without speech, the trade of life does not run.
And mere words, if unsold, remain hollow, while loud talkers gain prominence.
If speech is sweet like sugar, nectar dissolves in the heart and minds come together.
There is no cost involved in this sugar, yet humans show stinginess.
Who takes anything from a crow, and who gives to a cuckoo—by speaking sweet words, it steals the heart.
So keep sweetness and generosity in speech.
If you cannot give jaggery, at least speak words like jaggery.
But even from empty words, no bridge gets built.
The trader of mere talk beats the hollow conch.
Therefore speech must be tied to action; only then does the veil of life shine brightly.
In speech, if one does not consider the worthy and unworthy, then advice given to a monkey will only cause loss at home.
Words must be spoken after seeing the place and occasion, otherwise matters get spoiled.
Because of this, a story comes to mind.
The chieftain of forty villages built a war-fort.
The fort was tall and strong.
Seeking praise for its grandeur and a way out, he searched a lot but found nothing.
A Jat also came to see the fort.
After showing the fort, the guard asked him, “Patel, how do you find the fort?”
The Jat said, “The fort is very tall, but one thought comes to my mind: when the Thakur dies, where will they take him out for cremation?”
Hearing this, the Thakur became furious; his heart burst with rage.
“Such harsh words!” he said.
And had him put in the stocks.
The Patel’s elder son was sent to get his father released.
The son went and said, “Father, what need was there to speak such harsh words?”
“If they wished, the Thakurs could have cut and removed it.”
“Go drown like a buffalo in water.”
The son turned out to be even worse than the father.
He too was put in the stocks.
The second son came to get them released and said, “They are both fools.”
“What need was there to speak such bitter words?”
“If they wished, the Thakurs could have buried the fort inside the palace itself.”
“Well, this one too—subhanallah!”
He too was tied to the same stocks.
The Patel’s wife was very clever.
She covered her head with a veil and went to get all three released.
She went and said to the Thakur, “Three animals had come here.”
“Animals do not speak like humans; three animals had come to me.”
The Thakur understood that the Patel’s wife was very wise.
He released all three.
And rightly so.
God did not give speech to animals.
Speech was granted only to humans.
Disrespecting this gift is not right.
Without awareness of speech, a human behaves like an animal.
So one must maintain restraint in speaking and saying.
Speak only after seeing the deserving recipient.
Crying and wailing before everyone only brings mockery from the world.
Tell sorrow to the sorrowful—they will lessen half your pain; tell joy to the joyful—they will clap laughing.
Speech has its own limits.
Speech has its own code of conduct.
Do not lift the veil of speech before unworthy people, otherwise honor and dignity are lost.
The modesty of speech is no less than the modesty of a daughter-in-law or daughter.
The honor of speech is even higher than a married woman’s honor.
With speech, action must always walk together.
Both are twin sisters of Maya.
The bond of speech and action is the straight path to heaven.
The greater the gap between speech and action, the deeper the pit one falls into.
The enjoyment of speech has to be paid for by poor action.
The dowry spoken by speech has to be given by action.
“O Rahim, the tongue is mad; it speaks of heaven and hell—what it says outside comes back as blows upon the head.”
Therefore do not let the sisterhood of speech and action break.
Both are sisters of righteousness.
One brings shame, the other covers it.
One’s wound is healed by the other.
When the two unite, even poison turns into nectar.
Speech sweet like sugar, action bitter like poison; when speech and action become one, even poison becomes nectar.
Speak after deep thought, and act with balance.
Speech and action are the two pans of a balance, and thought is its beam.
On this balance, a human’s this world and the next are weighed.
One who keeps deceit in action is not wise, but blind.
When giving and taking in action remain balanced, trade and business follow the line of righteousness.
But nowadays it is such that, without becoming a grandfather, a child is rocked in the lap.
At the time of giving, a tiny illness arises.
It is not known that—
“A rope-climbing dancer says: none is truly a dancer; I became a dancer by dancing, the one who dances is the dancer.”
On one side is the miser, who does not even know the name of giving.
On the other side is the saint, who even while giving never becomes empty, never grows angry.
In his eyes, dust is gold, and gold is dust.
Mir, the disciple of Badshah Mohammed Shah, Munshi Ghananand, took to a life of asceticism and went to sit in Braj.
Intoxicated with Krishna’s love, he sang little songs.
But some informer, driven by jealousy, seeking revenge, finding an opportunity, secretly complained to the authorities that Delhi was being looted.
Then Mir Munshi Ghananand was sitting pressed down.
The soldiers of the informer went and said to Ghananand, “Tax, tax, tax.”
For Ghananand, Krishna’s name itself was wealth.
He threw three handfuls of Braj’s dust and said, “Dust, dust, dust.”
In the eyes of those lovers who are intoxicated with cups of love, whose only wealth is righteousness, gold is dust and the dust of Braj itself is gold.
But this is not the dharma of a householder.
In household life, both hands must be washed properly.
Give and take must go on evenly.
There should not be torn rags in the house, nor should there be a lack of cloth to cover a woman’s modesty.
Wandering in rags and waving the flag of dharma in the middle of the market—
this hypocrisy does not last.
A householder must collect what is due, settle accounts fully, and not run away far from responsibility under the pretext of tender-heartedness.
He must divide and bear both sides equally, like a saw cuts evenly on both sides.
Do not become foolish, do not be overly hard; keep the saw straight and the mind balanced in dividing and earning.
So in this way, when the wheels of speech and action move on the axle of thought,
the cart of human life runs smoothly and joy arises.
This is fine.
But who is the guide of this cart? There are a thousand paths, but the track is one.
That is the track of propriety.
And the track of honor.
When wealth decreases it is tolerable, but when honor decreases, truth also falls.
“People say the pot shrinks at the well, but how does it shrink? It shrinks only when the pot itself is broken.”
One who has no pot, what of his can shrink?
Only the nose of the noseless is cut; what is there to cut of the one already noseless?
Or else, there is another meaning of shrinking.
One whose pot is filled with hypocrisy has false honor; the path of social shame does not diminish him.
False honor, false social shame—honor does not reside in false superstitions.
Honor resides only within the pot itself.
The judgment of right and wrong happens only within the pot.
The inner soul present in every being alone gives judgment.
But who has seen this pot, this inner conscience?
If even doctors with machines that split lightning cannot see it, then how can we believe?
All right, Tarkeshwarji.
Your logic is being digested.
A simple, plain matter—how will it be digested, how will it appeal?
All your science is based on algebra and geometry.
In algebra you accept that a certain thing equals another—why do you accept it?
From where did it come?
In geometry, a point has no measure, no length or breadth,
yet why do you accept the existence of a point?
In stories there is a king and a queen, without any known address—why do you still accept their existence?
All these things are based on inference.
And the very foundation of science and knowledge is inference.
Therefore accept this inner pot as well.
Not only accept it—polish it, think upon it, refine it too.
In the words of poet Bihari: the eyes show the world, but the eyes themselves cannot be seen.
When the inner eye of knowledge opens, the whole game becomes visible.
Open this eye of knowledge.
Examine the pot and recognize it.
Building big palaces and mansions is meaningless if inside the heart the dirt of impurity lies pressed down.
What is achieved by diving into the Indian Ocean,
if one has never been soaked even for two moments in the nectar of love from the lake of the heart, and what great leap is that which has not crossed the distance between hearts?
Without wiping the tears from the moonlike face of a poor neighbor’s child, the zeal to touch the moon is false pride.
Before trying to manage divinity, manage the self.
Build the whole world, but first build yourself.
Only then will this human life become successful.
A sharp lightning flashed; when it struck the eyes, the eyelids blinked.
As if fire had spread across all the mountains.
With a rumbling sound, the clouds thundered.
The child pressed down in the bedding grabbed hold of his mother’s waist.
Lightning flashes began striking.
Along with thunder came Indra’s roar.
As if thousands of elephants were trumpeting together.
When the wind blew, it was such that it could tear off the roofs of houses; it came in a destructive form.
The violent wind started blowing fiercely.
Fences tied to posts loosened, pegs broke, and great chaos spread.
Hailstones began to fall rapidly in the low places.
Large hailstones fell as if gravel were raining down.
The flock of birds sitting on trees was scattered.
Wild animals from the hills hid their heads beneath bushes.
Beaten by rain, shivering with cold, people stumbled about, standing and sitting helplessly.
All living creatures became restless.
In the rocky hills, shepherds who had come to graze their animals
had built their huts far apart in the ravines.
In this storm, with black hail and wind, they crouched inside their huts.
It was the month of Paush.
Even otherwise the cold was severe, and today the hail-rain made it double.
Fires were lit to warm themselves.
Children did not leave their mothers.
Old men and women sat chanting “Ram Ram,” praying to Indra to reduce his fury.
In one hut was Amro Charan, bearing the burden of eighty years.
With rosary in hand, wrapped in a tattered quilt, he kept sliding the beads.
How could a torn quilt stop the cold? His hands kept trembling with cold.
His blue lips kept quivering.
The half-dead could not fall asleep.
Midnight—deep midnight.
The sound of horse hooves was heard.
The old man’s ears pricked up.
At this hour, a horse?
He heard the horse snort; the horse’s neigh was right near the hut door.
He rose in surprise.
He looked and saw the horse striking the ground at the door, neighing.
Who is there?
No answer.
Only the horse’s neighing.
There was a loud thud, as if someone had fallen.
Amro called out and went inside the hut.
“Daughter Ujali, get up and come out; I cannot see in the darkness.”
Shivering with cold, throwing aside the quilt, Ujali got up.
With the lantern, in its light Ujali’s body shone like the moon amid dark clouds.
She went out and in the lantern’s light saw the horse standing there.
Water was dripping from its body, and near the horse’s feet lay a rider fallen in a heap.
Unconscious, water dripping from his clothes, his whole body stiffened with cold, lips turned blue.
His whole body was rigid, lips blue, eyelids closed.
The old man quickly placed his hand on the rider’s chest; breathing was there, he felt the pulse—he was alive.
Groaning with effort, Ujali dragged him into the hut and laid him on the quilt.
“Uncle, is the rider alive?”
“He is alive, daughter, but he has stiffened from the cold.”
“Quick, light the fire.”
“We must warm him, otherwise he will die.”
“His lips have turned blue.”
“There is not a single piece of firewood in the house—what shall I light?”
She covered him with all the quilts in the house.
Worry lines appeared on Amro’s forehead: a traveler who came to the house might die.
The gravest sin of all is to neglect service to him.
He sank deep into thought.
Hardening his heart, placing his hand on Ujali’s head, he said,
“Daughter, if this rider dies, we ourselves will not even find a place in hell.”
“He must be given warmth.”
There is no firewood in the house, no quilts; I am an eighty-year-old man—where will warmth come from in my body?
There is one way, child; you are young.
If you give the warmth of your body to this rider, he will live.
Remove your clothes and let him sleep with you so that the warmth of your body enters his body.
The twenty-year-old unmarried girl kept looking at her father’s face.
“Daughter, this is duty, not sin”; lowering her head, Ujali obeyed.
Circled twice around the unconscious rider and, making God a witness,
“From today this foreign rider is my husband; I will sleep beside him to give warmth.”
“I will never forget your favor all my life,” the foreign rider said, holding Ujali’s hand.
Yesterday’s foreign rider today became one’s own, the master of Ujali’s inner being.
From the dark sky hail kept falling; the dark night turned into a night of union.
Above, in the sky, the moon was smiling; below, Meho Jethwo was rejoicing.
The prince of Porbandar, smiling, was filling Ujali’s heart with light.
Our meeting was a coincidence.
In the hills one finds the philosopher’s stone; in the forest one finds Shakuntala.
After forgetting Shakuntala, would King Dushyant sit anywhere at fairs?
Doubt arose in Ujali’s mind.
He would sit at fairs—but with Queen Ujali.
“Come, let us go together; take me with you.”
“Not like this.”
“I will come to marry you.”
“I will come with the thunder of drums, mounting thousands of horses.”
“Give me your promise.”
“Standing beneath the open sky, without witnesses, I take this vow.”
“I, Meho Jethwo, placed my hand in yours and made this great pledge.”
“Speak; you too make your vow from your true heart.”
Ujali vowed, “Through all births I am yours; apart from you, every other man in the world is my brother.”
“Whether you marry me or not, I have accepted you as my husband.”
“If the sun and moon deviate, then I will deviate.”
Days of happiness pass while talking; nights slip away quickly.
We were guests for only a few days.
One day, while tightening the saddle on the horse, Meho Jethwo asked for leave.
Ujali, sobbing, gave her consent.
Jethwo promised, “I will return within a fortnight.”
Jethwo would take permission from the king to hunt and come toward the hills on the pretext of hunting.
He would secretly meet Ujali.
For two hours in the day he would rest his head in Ujali’s lap, easing the fatigue of mind and body.
Sitting in nights of union, they planned their marriage.
Making ornaments of forest flowers from the hills, he would adorn Ujali.
Before the flowers could wither, with his heart heavy, he would return to his camp and sleep in the torn grass hut.
In moments of union they spoke heart to heart, but the naked sword of separation always hung overhead.
Thus months passed.
The matter remained hidden for some days.
The king came to know; people came to know.
The king became enraged.
Talk began spreading among the subjects.
